<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Fully Implement Peace Accord in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government vowed
Tuesday to pursue the full implementation of a 1996 peace
agreement it forged with the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)
with or without Nur Misuari as the governor of the Autonomous
Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM).
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre made this clear as
he said efforts to develop Mindanao must be based on institutions,
and not on personalities.
</P>
<P>
"We should pursue the peace agreement because it is beyond
personalities. We continue our obligations there, these are our
obligations to our people in the Muslim areas," Aguirre said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that pushing through with the government-MNLF
peace process despite the problem regarding Misuari would be one
of his recommendations to President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Misuari has remained abroad after attending the OIC meeting
where he and Aguirre presented clashing views on the government's
implementation of the 1996 peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, also chair of the MNLF, accused the government of
reneging on its promise under the 1996 agreement to implement a
meaningful autonomy for Muslims in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre, who came from the 27th foreign ministers conference of
the OIC in Kuala Lumpur, said Misuari deserved to be censured not
only for his conduct during the OIC meeting, but also for his
failure to perform his functions as governor.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said it is also likely that Misuari would be forced to
step down as ARMM governor by September as President Estrada would
be given a free hand to appoint somebody else as interim governor
until the elections in May 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
