<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif Denies Knowledge About Party Leader's Talks With Musharraf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's deposed prime minister
Nawaz Sharif has said that he was not aware of meetings between
Pakistan's military ruler General Pervez Musharraf and the acting
leader of his Pakistan Muslim League (PML) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen at the Attock Fort Accountability Court,
which is in the proximity of Islamabad, on Tuesday, Sharif refused
to confirm that Raja Zafar ul Haq sought his permission for the
meeting and simply stated that he was not aware of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, he said PML, the former ruling party, will remain
united and it will be impossible for any person to divide it.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister, who has been rewarded life
imprisonment in a hijacking case, is being tried in a corruption
case.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf, chief executive of Pakistan, on Monday
started meetings with the country's leading political leaders in a
move to bridge the gulf between the regime and the parties.
</P>
<P>
His meeting with Haq, the No. 2 person in PML only second to
Sharif who is in jail, was his first meeting with any PML leader
since the military coup in October last year.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting Haq said he will inform Sharif of the meeting.
"Of course, I cannot tell all," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
