<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Government Calls for Self-Censorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government Tuesday
called for media organizations to exercise self-censorship
following a reintroduced censorship on the local and foreign media.
</P>
<P>
However, "if you have any doubt on any articles before they
being published send those to the censor board for scrutiny," said
Director of Information Ariya Rubasinghe, the chief censor.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka on Monday reintroduced censorship on the local and
foreign media under an extraordinary gazette notification issued
by President Chandrika Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruled last Friday that the blanket censorship
imposed on May 3 when Tamil Tiger rebels stepped up attacks in the
northern Jaffna peninsula was illegal as the censor was not
properly appointed.
</P>
<P>
Rubasinghe said that censorship is necessary since the
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) and government
troops were poised for a major confrontation in Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The notification said all war-related news and whatever else
the government considered to be against national interests or
detrimental to the preservation of public order would be covered
under the new censorship.
</P>
<P>
It said media could not report military operations, procurement
of arms, details of deployment of troops, or news that might
affect the morale of the troops.
</P>
<P>
Institutions violating the new sets of the regulations will be
punished according to the new gazette notification, said
Rubasinghe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sri Lanka tightened security in Colombo on Tuesday
amid reports that some 25 LTTE's suicide bombers, known as Black
Tigers, had infiltrated the capital to assassinate political
leaders ahead of the 13th anniversary of the first suicide mission
carried out by a Black Tiger.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels staged their first suicide attack on July 5,
1987 when a rebel called Captain Miller drove a truck packed with
explosives and devastated the Nelliyadi army camp in the Jaffna
peninsula, killing some 40 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
