<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Albright Discuss Trilateral Summit on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Wednesday discussed over telephone with United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright a planned U.S.-Palestinian-Israeli summit
aimed at pushing forward the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone conversation initiated by Albright, she
briefed Mubarak on U.S. President Bill Clinton's announcement that
a trilateral summit will be held near Washington to seek a
breakthrough in the peace negotiations, Egypt's official Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced at the White House earlier in the day that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak will meet with him next week at the presidential retreat of
Camp David to try to reach a final peace agreement by mid-
September.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Albright also exchanged views on a number of issues
under discussion between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have set September 13 as the target
date to finally resolve the thorniest issues including borders,
Jerusalem, refugees, Jewish settlements and water. The two sides
have made little progress.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel
in 1979, plays an active role in mediating between the Palestinians
and the Jewish state. 
</P>
