<HEADLINE> U.S. Soccer Team Refused Entry by Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. soccer team was banned
from entering Tehran as a retaliation for the fingerprinting of
Iranians visiting the United States.
</P>
<P>
Bahram Afsharzadeh, deputy of Iran's Physical Education
Organization, said Wednesday that the Foreign Ministry intervened
to bar the Americans from playing in a July 9-11 tournament on
Kish, a resort island in the southern Gulf and one of three
Iranian free-trade zones.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Iran would hold the tournament at a later,
undisclosed date without the American team, which is two divisions
below Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
Afsharzadeh said Iran wanted improved sports contacts with the
United States but said "America's unfriendly behavior" was an
obstacle.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to welcome American teams and treat them in a
friendly and civilized way and we expect the same from the
Americans," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Fingerprinting Iranians is considered an insult against the
Iranian nation. We expect the United States to waive the
fingerprinting formality and show respect for Iranians to allow
improved sports contacts," he explained.
</P>
<P>
U.S. immigration officials waived the fingerprinting formality
in January to allow a soccer match between the two countries in
Pasadena, California, but only after Iran threatened to cancel the
match.
</P>
<P>
Last month, seven Iranian women refused to be fingerprinted
upon arriving in New York to attend a U.N. conference and returned
home after U.S. immigration officials insisted on the procedure.
</P>
<P>
Several Iranian groups have called on the Iranian government to
retaliate by fingerprinting Americans upon their arrival in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. law requires non-immigrant visitors from four
countries with whom it has strained ties -- Iran, Iraq, Libya and
Sudan -- to be fingerprinted and photographed on arrival in the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
