<HEADLINE> Poll: More Germans Turn Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Germans are losing patience with
the weak euro and only 31 percent of them are in favor of the
common European currency, a poll organization said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Institute for Public Opinion Research based in Allenbach
reported some 50 percent Germans had turned against euro in a
latest poll among 2,113 plain Germans.
</P>
<P>
In east Germany, 60 percent of the people asked gave a
negative comment on euro, while in western states the number was
47 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only 21 percent of the respondents said they trusted the euro
"much" or "very much." A year ago, the number was 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
That made a sharp contrast to the period between year 1997 and
year 1999, when the number of euro-favorites grew from 21 percent
to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The institute attributed the turning of public impression of
euro to its long-standing weakness that compelled Germans to pay
more for imported goods and overseas traveling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Economy, Still Rich Country Phenomenon: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the process of concentration of "knowledge power," will the
first-mover advantage gained by the more advanced players become
irreversible? asked the report prepared by the U.N. Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The answer to the question is being given by delegates to a
three-day high-level meeting of the U.N. Economic and Social
Council, themed "development and international cooperation in the
21st century: the role of information technology (IT) in the
context of a knowledge-based global economy."
</P>
<P>
Differential access to the Internet is much more pronounced
than national income inequalities across the world, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Figures and facts show that the fifth of the world's people
living in the highest income countries have 86 percent of the
world's GDP but 93 percent of Internet users, while the bottom
fifth have 1 percent of GDP and only 0.2 percent of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
The digital divide is also reflected in the production of
information technology, with 55 countries now accounting for 99
percent of world spending on IT production.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the ongoing process of globalization helps to
consolidate the first-mover advantage of the developed nations,
thus making it difficult for developing countries to reap real
benefits from the production of IT.
</P>
<P>
The distribution of Internet bandwidth is another indicator of
the differential access, as more than 98 percent of global
bandwidth at the inter-regional level is currently connected to
North America.
</P>
<P>
North America, especially the United States, operates as the
hub of Internet traffic while developing countries have to make
payments for traffic exchange and connectivity to U.S.
telecommunications carriers.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement merely exacerbates the differential access to
IT in the context of developing nations' foreign exchange
constraints.
</P>
<P>
Unless radical and decisive action is taken, the differential
access to information and knowledge will become much more acute,
said the report, which called for collaborative effort involving
governments, multilateral and bilateral donors as market forces
cannot solve the problem alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robust Growth Expected for Asia-Pacific Data Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The deployment of data
communications in Asia-Pacific, excluding Japan, is expected to
remain strong throughout the next five years, a U.S. market
research firm predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Given the resiliency witnessed between 1998 and 1999, the
overall data communications market, including network adapters,
hubs, switches, routers, remote access servers and WAN switches,
in the region is expected to reach 9 billion U.S. dollars by 2004,
an annual growth rate of 23 percent in five years.
</P>
<P>
The research firm International Data Corporation (IDC)
attributed the growth to continuing economic resurgence, renewed
investments by both government sector and enterprise,
telecommunications industry liberation and substantial increases
in Internet usage.
</P>
<P>
Aided by the strong growth in switches and routers, IDC said,
the LAN market for the region is likely to see robust growth of 18
percent over the forecast period to reach 5.8 billion dollars by
2004. In terms of products, switches will continue to remain the
fastest-growing segment and reach 3.3 billion dollars in 2004.
</P>
<P>
The region's remote access market is expected to more than
quadruple in the next five years, from 300 million dollars in 1999
to 1.4 billion dollars in 2004. Lack of an installed base in
emerging markets coupled with voice and data convergence trends
throughout the region will be the primary market drivers,
according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
China will remain one the key growth markets in the region, IDC
said. Australia and South Korea will continue to be the major
markets due to growing opportunity in the telecommunications and
Internet sectors. India will be the fatest-growing country and its
contribution to the region is expected to grow rapidly with the
opening up of the Internet industry and thus likely increased
awareness and demand for leading-edge technologies, IDC added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
