<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Signs Two Protocols on Child Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Wednesday singed at the Headquarters of the United Nations in
New York two U.N. protocols on child rights.
</P>
<P>
The two protocols, adopted by the United Nations General
Assembly in May, are the Optional Protocol to the Convention on
the Rights of the Child on the sale of children, child
prostitution and child pornography and the Optional Protocol to
the Convention on the Rights of the Child on the involvement of
children in armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
The optional protocol on the sale of children, child
prostitution and child pornography focuses on the criminalization
of these violations of children's rights and emphasizes the need
for increased public awareness and international cooperation in
efforts to combat them.
</P>
<P>
The optional protocol on the involvement of children in armed
conflict, among other provisions, makes 18 the minimum age for
compulsory induction into the armed forces. Fifteen is the current
minimum age.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the signing ceremony, U.N. Deputy Secretary-General,
Frechette Louise, expressed the hope that the United States would
also be able to ratify these protocols and, of course, ratify the
Convention on the Rights of Child.  
</P>
</TEXT>
