<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Appeals Court Upholds Former Islamic Premier's Imprisonment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Appeals Court Wednesday
upheld a one-year imprisonment sentence imposed on Necmettin
Erbakan, former prime minister and leader of the outlawed Islamic
Welfare Party, Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The court unanimously approved the sentence, which was made by
the Diyarbakir State Security Court (DGM) for "inciting hatred and
animosity among people on the basis of racial, religious and social
class differences."
</P>
<P>
Erbakan took office as prime minister in June 1996. One year
later, he was forced to resign under heavy pressures from the
powerful military and other parties, which accused his pro-Islamic
cabinet of implementing anti-secular domestic and foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
In January 1998, the Constitutional Court ordered the closure of
the Welfare Party for its violation of secularism stipulated in the
constitution, while Erbakan and other leaders of the party were
banned from politics for a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
Overwhelmingly Muslim Turkey sticks to secular, democratic and
nationalist principles, set up by the republic's founder Kemal
Ataturk.
</P>
<P>
The DGM charged Erbakan with instigating religious hatred in a
speech which he delivered in eastern Bingol province on February
25, 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Erbakan said that "laws in Turkey will be made by
infidels, who do not allow women to wear headscarf. We will not be
slaves to the Christians. We will be for the World Islamic Union."
</P>
<P>
Erbakan was also criticized for opposing Turkey's efforts to
join the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Erbakan's lawyers said on Wednesday that they would request a "
correction of verdict" after the appeals court notifies the
ratification.
</P>
<P>
Naci Unver, head of the appeals court's criminal department,
said that Erbakan has the right to apply for a "correction of
verdict", but his application needs to be approved by the court's
prosecutor's office. If approved, the application will then be
reviewed by the court's criminal department.
</P>
<P>
If the prosecutor's office overturns his appeal, the legal
procedure will be completed and Erbakan will be put behind bars.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Bulent Arinc, acting chairman of the pro-
Islamic opposition Virtue Party's Deputies Group, said,"Turkey can
not and should not put a former prime minister in prison in 2000s."
</P>
<P>
"I felt profound sorrow and shame. Imprisonment of a person at
the age of 75 who served Turkey as a prime minister, due to a
sentence in his speech, will put Turkey in a difficult situation in
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of Virtue Party Mehmet Bekaroglu said at a press
briefing that the approval was made to detach people's attention
over the government's failed efforts to curb the chronic inflation,
which is putting a strain on the public.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was implementing a three-year economic stability program,
in which the government promised to reduce inflation to 20 percent
in 2000, 10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
But the annual inflation still stood at 58.6 percent in June of
this year, down from 68.9 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
He said that this move will put Turkey in a "bad" position in
front of the world, and negatively affect Turkey's accession
process to the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
