<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Daily Oil Export Tops 2.45 Million Barrels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- With an increase in oil production
starting July 1, Iran's oil export has topped 2.45 million barrels
per day (bpd) this month, an oil official announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in production and export is in line with the
agreement reached among members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) in June, said Deputy Managing Director
of the National Iranian Oil Company Hojatollah Qanimifard.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Iran will coordinate its policies with other
OPEC members to stabilize the international oil market, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil ministers agreed to raise the organization's oil output
ceiling by 708,000 bpd to reach 25.4 million bpd in their June
meeting in Vienna. Iraq was excluded from the agreement as it is
under U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with its quota within the OPEC agreement, Iran
announced on July 1 that it would increase the output by 104,000
bpd from the original level of some 3.7 million barrels. All the
increased will be exported.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the second largest producer after Saudi Arabia within
OPEC, is opposed to increasing output by a large scale, maintaining
that the oil supply to the world market is not so insufficient as
some people have calculated.
</P>
<P>
On the high oil price in the U.S. market, Qanimifard said it was
due to the need for new gasoline or the so-called "green gasoline"
as well as a lack of refinery facilities for the product.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Iran's Oil Ministry also expressed its opposition to
unilateral output hike by OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members have decided a legal output hike through their
agreement, so there is no reason for any member state to
unilaterally make extra increase in production, an unnamed official
from the ministry was quoted by IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official also denied reports that Saudi Arabia would
increase output unilaterally by 500,000 bpd to reduce the oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that under the U.S. pressure, Saudi Arabia was
planning in conjunction with other producers to raise output in a
matter of days if high prices do not come down to satisfactory
levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
