<HEADLINE> Tehran, Cairo in Agreement on Expanding Ties: Iranian MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Amid a thaw in the relations frozen
for more than two decades, a senior Iranian parliamentary official
said here on Wednesday his country and Egypt are in agreement on
boosting bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have been taking steps aimed at expanding the
bilateral ties, Mohsen Mirdamadi, chairman of the Iranian
parliament's foreign affairs committee, said after meeting with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Mirdamadi, who was leading Iran's delegation to an Islamic
parliaments conference in Cairo, also said the bilateral ties are
proceeding in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
Iran severed its diplomatic ties with Egypt after the latter
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979 and then gave shelter to
the former Shah, who was deposed in Iran's Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Joint efforts exerted in the past few years have significantly
improved the ties.
</P>
<P>
Moussa met Mirdamadi after talks in Kuala Lumpur last week with
Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on the sidelines of a
foreign ministers meeting of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said last Sunday Egypt and Iran have held high-level
talks aimed at normalizing the ties, which he added "are making
progress."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, on June 21, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami held a telephone conversation in
the first direct contact between leaders of the two countries since
1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
