<HEADLINE> Barak Says He Will Attend Three-way Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said on Wednesday he will attend a three-way summit slated for next
week in the United States to try to work out a peace agreement with
the Palestinians ahead of a September target for a final peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Israeli Embassy in Paris, Barak told reporters
that "this is undoubtedly an important moment in the history of the
attempt to solve the conflict between us and the Palestinians,"
reported Israeli Radio on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I will take my place at the head of our delegation to Camp
David next week with a heavy feeling of responsibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced at the White House on
Wednesday he will call the summit with Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat early next week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat will also attend the summit, a senior
palestinian official said in the same day.
</P>
<P>
"We committed to (U.S. Secretary of State) Madeleine Albright
when she came here that when President Clinton invites us to a
summit we would accept, and we accepted," Palestinian cabinet
Minister of International Cooperation Nabil Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
Barak was in Paris to hold talks with French President Jacques
Chirac on the Middle East peace process after visiting British
Prime Minister Tony Blair in London earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Barak was due to return home later on Wednesday. 
