<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Calls for Lifting of U.N. Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will do its best to urge
the United Nations to lift the sanctions imposed on Iraq ever since
its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, Pakistani Minister of Oil and Natural
Resources Ausman Amien Al-Dien said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dien made the remarks while meeting with Iraqi Vice President
Taha Yassin Ramadan, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Al-Dien criticized the continuation of the
sanctions, saying Pakistan will make efforts to alleviate the
sufferings of the Iraqi people, who have been the hardest hit by
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani minister expressed willingness to promote economic
cooperation between Pakistan and Iraq, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ramadan appreciated the stand of Pakistan and
condemned the continued aggressions of the United States and
Britain against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The aggressive policy by the U.S. and Britain against Iraq
constitutes gross violations of the international law and the U.N.
Charter, Ramadan said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes have been enforcing the two no-fly
zones in southern and northern Iraq, with the claimed aim of
protecting Kurds in the north and Shiite Muslims in the south from
the so-called persecution by the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dien arrived in the Iraqi capital Baghdad on Sunday evening
for a visit aimed at closer bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Pakistan have been intensifying efforts to strengthen
bilateral relations. Pakistani Commerce Minister Abdul Razzak Daud
visited Iraq in February, saying his country is prepared to
renovate Iraq's electrical and oil installations, which have become
dilapidated after the decade-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is ready to supply Iraq with products and goods under
the U.N. oil-for-food accord," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's electrical and oil facilities were severely damaged
during the 1991 Gulf War, and repairs have been hampered by a lack
of spare parts because of the U.N. sanctions imposed on the country
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions are partly alleviated by the oil-for-food deal
which went into effect in December 1996 and allows Iraq to export
limited quantities of oil in order to purchase daily necessities
under U.N. supervision.
</P>
<P>
Part of that income goes toward the rebuilding of Iraq's
electrical and oil sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
