<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Welcomes President's Call for Reconciliation Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Head of the Sudanese opposition
National Democratic Alliance (NDA) Mohamed Othman Merghani on
Wednesday welcomed the Sudanese president's call for a meeting
within a month between the Sudanese government and NDA members.
</P>
<P>
President Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir called late last month for
a meeting between the government and the opposition under an
Egyptian-Libyan peace initiative, which was proposed last year and
demands permanent ceasefire and a peace conference aimed at
realizing national reconciliation and ending a 17-year civil war in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inaugural session of a two-day meeting in Cairo,
Merghani said the Egyptian-Libyan initiative forms the basis for
realizing peace between the Sudanese government and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The NDA comprises Sudan's northern Muslim political parties,
which want to share power with el-Bashir's government, and southern
rebel groups, mainly the Sudan People's Liberation Army, which has
been fighting for greater autonomy for the mostly Christian and
animist southern states. About two million people have died in the
war and war-related disasters. It has an office in the Egyptian
capital.
</P>
<P>
Merghani spoke highly of the efforts exerted by Egypt and Libya
in seeking a peaceful solution to the Sudanese problem and bringing
the viewpoints of the two warring sides closer.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the NDA's stance toward an overall political
solution to the Sudanese issue for stemming bloodshed and
realization of a just and comprehensive peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been keen on mediating a peace agreement between the
Sudanese government and the opposition, for fear that a possible
disintegration of the southern neighbor will jeopardize its major
water source, the Nile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
