<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Completing First Plant Genome Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Scientists are expected to
complete the first plant genome map by the end of July, according
to a report in the latest issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
The report said that an international research team had
sequenced 108 million nucleotide bases of the 120-million-base
Arabidopsis, a wispy, ankle-high mustard plant, by the end of June.
And the genetic information is publicly available.
</P>
<P>
The five participating international groups hope to finish the
genome mapping job by the end of July, well ahead of the original
2004 target date.
</P>
<P>
Government funders and sequencers boast that the Arabidopsis
genome is extremely accurate, with only one error in every 20,000
bases, and contains few gaps, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Although its completion will mark the first detailed genetic
record of a plant, scientists say, the real value will be as a
template for the rice genome, some four times larger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Hold Three-Way Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced Wednesday that he will host a summit with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at Camp
Davis, Maryland, early next week in a bid to deal with difficult
core issues on the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
"The objective (of the summit) is to reach an agreement on the
core issues that have fueled a half century of conflict between
Israelis and Palestinians," Clinton said at a White house briefing.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed an intense effort by Clinton and his
advisers to bring the parties together. Clinton talked to Barak
and Arafat on the phone last week to persuade them to agree to a
summit at Camp Davis, a presidential retreat where Egypt and
Israel held a summit with President Jimmy Carter in 1978.
</P>
<P>
"After lengthy discussion with the two leaders and after
listening to Secretary Albright's report, I have concluded that
this is the best way -- indeed, it is the only way -- to move
forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright had made a trip to the Middle East region late last
month to assess the possibility of a three-way Mideast summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted, "The negotiators have reached an impasse.
Movement now depends on historic decisions that only the two
leaders can make."
</P>
<P>
But he warned that "there is clearly no easy answers, and
certainly no painless ones, and therefore, there is clearly no
guarantee of success."
</P>
<P>
The Israelis and Palestinians agreed last year to set September
13 as the deadline for the two sides to work out a final status
pact. But three rounds of talks since early this year have so far
failed to narrow their differences even for a framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said he will declare a Palestinian state even if the
negotiations have not been conclusive on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Barak warned Wednesday that Israel would act unilaterally if
the Palestinians made any unilateral moves to declare an
independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
