<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Fall In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of Leading
Economic Indicators fell in May, showing a new sign of slowdown in
the U.S. economy after six hikes in interest rates, the Conference
Board said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a prominent business research group, said
in a survey that the composite index declined by 0.1 percent to
106 in May after no change in April and a 0.1 percent rise in
March. It stood at 100 in 1996, its base year.
</P>
<P>
"The modest pace in the Leading Indicators in recent months
clearly indicates some loss of momentum in the pace of economic
activity," said Conference Board Economist Ken Goldstein. "The
signals now point to sustained expansion, but not at the rapid
pace we saw at the start of 2000."
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the U.S. economic activity was in response to
the monetary tightening. The Federal Reserve has raised interest
rates six times in the past year in an effort to steer the economy
toward a moderate growth rate of between 3.5 percent and 4 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
The survey also reported that the Coincident Index rose 0.2
percent in May after a 0.3 percent rise in April, showing some
strength still left in the economy. Gains in employment, income
and industrial production continue to drive the Coincident Index
ahead, even as the Leading Indicators point to a more modest pace
of expansion, it added.
</P>
<P>
The survey said the Lagging Index also rose by 0.2 percent in
May after a 0.5 percent increase in April and no change in March.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index of Leading Economic Indicators was a key
gauge of the U.S. economic activity, forecasting economic trends
for the next three to six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Meets on Bringing Benefits of IT Revolution to Developing World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Bringing the benefits of the
information technology (IT) revolution to the developing world was
a formidable take and it faced major difficulties in the areas of
connectivity, capacity and content, said a senior U.N. official
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the high-level meeting on information
and communication technologies and development organized by the
United Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC), U.N. Deputy
Secretary-General Frechette Louise said the digital resolution
held great promise for economic growth, poverty eradication and
development.
</P>
<P>
It had already brought extraordinary benefits to the developed
world, and it could improve the chances for poor countries to
leapfrog some long and painful stages in the development process,
thereby saving considerable time and resources, Frechette said.
</P>
<P>
"Information technology is empowering only when it is easily
and cheaply accessible. So the question is how to ensure IT access
for the poor," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Capacity means not just the computers to connect to the
Internet, but the technological skills needed to use IT facilities
and service them. Technological literacy is a must," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The third obstacle is content, which must be relevant to
local needs. Because the majority of hosts are located in the
developed world, the information available reflects the interests
of the population in that part of the world. In addition, 80
percent of the material currently on the Internet is in English, a
language that 75 percent of the world's people do not speak. The
creation of both local and automatic translation technologies must
be encouraged," the deputy secretary-general noted.
</P>
<P>
The high-level meeting, to be held from July 5 to 7, will be
focus on the measures to overcome the lag in IT use in the less
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The ECOSOC meeting is expected to issue a ministerial-level
declaration which will endorse a global action plan involving the
U.N., international agencies, countries and the private sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
