<HEADLINE> U.N. Reports Full Ugandan Withdrawal From Kisangani </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan forces have
completed their withdrawal from Kisangani, the third largest city
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), a United Nations
spokesman said here.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a press
conference here that the Ugandan troops left the DRC city by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Four Ugandan battalions had withdrawn to the city of Banalia,
about 100 kilometers north of Kisangani," Silva said, citing the
report from the U.N. Mission in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, who jointly put Kisangani under
their control, last month agreed to withdraw to positions at least
100 kilometers outside Kisangani after fighting each other for a
week in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandan troop withdrawal was confirmed by the U.N.
Mission on June 21," he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda back rival factions fighting the DRC
president, Laurent Kabila, supported by Angola, Namibia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, troops from the rebel Rally for Congolese Democracy
(RCD) are refusing to withdraw from Kisangani as stipulated in a U.
N. Security Council resolution, he said.
</P>
<P>
The refusal came "in violation of the latest Security Council
resolution calling for the demilitarization of the city," the
spokesman said. 
</P>
