<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Wednesday
pledged another 100 million euro (95 million U.S. dollars) for the
Chernobyl Shelter Fund.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made in Berlin at the second pledging conference
which aimed at providing the necessary funds to rehabilitate the
sarcophagus sheltering reactor 4 of the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant.
</P>
<P>
"This very substantial EU effort is fully in line with repeated
expressions of the EU in support of Chernobyl," said Christopher
Patten, EU external relations commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The union has so far provided Ukraine with 350 million euro (
332.5 million dollars) as special funds for Chernobyl and
Chernobyl-related projects.
</P>
<P>
The commission believes that the potential danger associated
with the damaged unit will persist until the highly radioactive
material contained under the existing sarcophagus shelter is
permanently isolated from the environment.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian authorities announced earlier in the year that
they are closing definitely the last operating nuclear reactor at
Chernobyl on December 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
"The recent decision of President Kuchma and the Ukrainian
government to stick to the commitment made under the 1995
Memorandum of Understanding with the G-7 and to definitely shut
down the last operating reactor at Chernobyl on 15 December 2000
paved the way for continued substantial support by the
international community and the EU," said Patten. 
</P>
