<HEADLINE> The Netherlands to Auction UMTS Phone Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands is scheduled to
auction Thursday third-generation UMTS mobile telephone licenses,
reports reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On offer will be five UMTS mobile phone licenses. UMTS stands
for universal mobile telecommunications standard, the newest
generation of cellular phone service. UMTS boasts of a
transmission speed 40 times faster than that of the existing GSM
standard.
</P>
<P>
The higher telecommunication speed makes possible new
capabilities such as mobile phone connection to the Internet and
video displays.
</P>
<P>
Eight companies have been allowed into the scheduled auction,
including five already having established telecoms services in the
Netherlands. The bidders are KPN Mobile, Libertel, Telfort,
Dutchtone, Ben, Nogenta Swedish Acquisition, Hutchison 3G
Netherlands and VersaTel.
</P>
<P>
KPN Mobile and Libertel are the largest and second largest
mobile phone operators in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The opening price for the auction has been set at a total of
470 million Dutch guilders (202 million U.S. dollars). Dutch
Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm said that he expected an auction
yield of some 20 billion guilders (19 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Dutch Treasury has canceled a July bond issue because of
anticipated UMTS license revenues.
</P>
<P>
In April, the British government got 22.5 billion pounds (34
billion U.S. dollars) from the auction sales of five UMTS licenses,
more than five times the sum formerly expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
