<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Warns Austria on Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission warned
Wednesday that Austria could become an even bigger pariah if the
scheduled referendum decided to block EU decisions.
</P>
<P>
If Austria blocked European Union legislation or reforms, that
is only counterproductive and will backfire, said Peter Guilford,
spokesman for the European Commission, the executive body of the
15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Federal Chancellor Wolfgang Schussel announced Tuesday
that his country will hold a referendum to show popular anger with
the political sanctions imposed by Austria's 14 other EU partners
since early February.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed as a protest against Austria's
incorporation of the far-right Freedom Party into the governing
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Austria asked the European Union summit held last month at
Feira of Portugal to consider lifting the sanctions but was
refused consideration.
</P>
<P>
Austria warned to consult with public opinion about whether to
use its veto right to block the functioning of the union in
retaliation against the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
One of the six questions to be included in the referendum will
be: "Should the (Austrian) federal government ensure with all
possible means that the unfairly imposed sanctions on Austria from
the other members of the European Union be lifted immediately?"
</P>
<P>
"We don't think a referendum is going to bring a solution,"
said the European Commission spokesman. "If a referendum is held,
we would deeply regret it."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman cited as a useless example the British vetoing EU
decisions for several months in 1996 after its beef exports had
been banned due to the outbreak of madcow disease.
</P>
<P>
Yet EU observers believe that Austria can do considerable
damage with its power to veto EU decisions that need support of
all 15 member governments.
</P>
<P>
Austria's support will be critical to such EU decisions as
enlargement to include 12 eastern and southern European countries
into the union and institutional reforms to overhaul the EU's
decision-making mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
