<HEADLINE> Wages of Zimbabwean Clothing Workers Increased by 47.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Workers in Zimbabwe's clothing
industry have been awarded a 47.5 percent wage increase with
effect from the beginning of this month, an official said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the National Union of the Clothing
Industry Fredy Mpofu told reporters that negotiations with
employers for the wage increase were concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The 47.5 percent is an addition to the 10 percent cost of
living adjustment awarded at the beginning of May," he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 47.5 percent increment, 6 percent would be effected in
February next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, despite the increment, workers are
still concerned with the future of the industry which he described
as hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
The influx of second-hand and new clothes from countries such
as Mauritius are threatening the viability of the local industry,
he said, noting that "the shortage of foreign currency in the
country is worsening the situation because the local industry
cannot afford to import special raw materials."
</P>
<P>
He said people now prefer imports which are of good quality and
sold at a cheaper price.
</P>
<P>
"Out government has to take steps to protect the local industry
because a large number of people will lose their jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean clothing industry, which has been on the
downturn for the past few years due to economic difficulties, has
a workforce of over 20,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
