<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Launch National Hygiene Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government is to launch
a participatory hygiene and sanitation transformation (PHAST)
program to involve the participation of the rural population in
the improvement of their hygiene and sanitation, Rwanda News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Katabarwa, an official in charge of public health in the
Ministry of Health, said the PHAST approach would teach and
stimulate the public on hygiene and sanitation concepts but more
importantly, it will enable people to overcome the constraints of
behavioral change.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the PHAST program will achieve a lot
 especially at the village level, where hygiene and sanitation are
at stake.
</P>
<P>
As more village health committees are formed, there will be an
increased awareness and knowledge of hygiene and health matters at
household and community levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
PHAST is also intended to deal with issues related to
environmental health, Katabarwa said, noting that the program has
been successful in such countries as Botswana, Kenya, Uganda and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The participatory hygiene and sanitation transformation
methodology was first initiated by the World Health Organization
and the Regional Water and Sanitation Groups for East and Southern
Africa in 1993. 
</P>
