<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Education Makes Remarkable Progress: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's education has made
considerable progress in the past five years following the
government's big and successive investment into the field, a
senior official told Xinhua here on Wednesday in an exclusive
interview.
</P>
<P>
The annual education budget of the state has increased from
about 500 million birr (one U.S. dollar equals 8.12 birr) in 1996
to nearly 2.5 billion birr in the fiscal year 1999/2000, said the
country's Vice Education Minister Teklehaimanot Haileselassie.
</P>
<P>
He said of the total national budget, the education portion has
 accounted for 14 percent from 9 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the enrollment of primary school pupils has also
more than doubled from about 20 percent to some 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total enrollment of students in primary and secondary
schools as well as universities and schools of higher learning in
Ethiopia has come up to more than 6 million by last fiscal year
from 2 million five years ago, Haileselassie said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the remarkable progress to the priority that the
government has given to the education field.
</P>
<P>
"The Ethiopian government has considered education as a very
much important area to eliminate poverty and to develop national
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said to popularize education, private schools have been
encouraged for years by the government, which has given effective
support to the effort to promote national education.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice minister, dozens of Ethiopian graduate
students are being sent abroad annually to take master and doctor
courses in an effort to speed up training of senior intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
Many people, who were conferred doctorate abroad, are playing
an important role in state construction, he said, noting that some
have filled in the gaps in the teaching and scientific research
fields in Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
