<HEADLINE> Angola Sets New Planks for Peace Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has set new
planks for its "peace platform", focusing on the respect for the
Lusaka Peace Protocol and ruling out the possibility of any
mediation in the civil conflicts, informed sources told Xinhua
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the new planks were set out by
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos during Monday's meeting
of the Council of Republic, a consultation organization for the
president.
</P>
<P>
The new planks emphasized that peace with the rebels led by
Jonas Savimbi should be based on the respect for the Lusaka accord
signed by all belligerents last July, the collapse of which led to
the renewed civil war last year.
</P>
<P>
The other three clauses are to revise the ongoing
constitutional and electoral law, to hold elections as soon as
appropriate conditions are created and to reintegrate all rebels
who abandoned their weapons, the sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The government must base its actions "on discussion, openness,
and regular, permanent and fruitful dialogue with all sectors of
society", the sources quoted Santos as saying.
</P>
<P>
The president also ruled out any possibility of mediation in
the country' s civil conflict, saying the government must continue
to act as the " protagonist" in conducting the peace process and
"not allow this part of its power to be transferred to the hands
of others". 
</P>
</TEXT>
