<HEADLINE> WFP Urges Rapid Response to Drought in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
appealed here Wednesday for 88 million U.S. dollars to feed 3.3
million starving Kenyans from August to December this year.
</P>
<P>
"We need international donors to quickly pledge food and cash
to address the spiralling needs," said David Fletcher, WFP's
Deputy Country Director for Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"We're doing everything possible to have sufficient food for
people in July, but we've absolutely nothing in-hand for the month
of August, which spells potential disaster for tens of thousands
of people relying on our help," said Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
The increased food aid needs were announced last month as part
of an overall U.N. appeal for 13.4 million drought victims in the
Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The number of Kenyans in need of food aid are second only to
Ethiopia where 10 million people rely on relief food.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya is really struggling to cope with this drought which has
hit the entire Horn of Africa," said Fletcher, adding "millions
of people throughout the country have never managed to recover
from an almost non- stop string of devastating droughts and floods
during the 1990s."
</P>
<P>
Fletcher noted that the failure of the March to May rainy
season has deteriorated the situation throughout the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
In the worst-hit areas, about 80 percent of livestock have
died. Crops have withered, and people are selling their few
remaining possessions at throw-away prices.
</P>
<P>
For pastoralists, it takes years for livestock herds to be
replenished. This means that large quantities of relief food may
be required for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure that the most vulnerable people receive
food, a new streamlined system has been established with greater
community participation in Kenya, according to the WFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
