<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Seeks Ban on Sierra Leone Diamonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council,
after several days of delay, hopes Wednesday to adopt a resolution
to impose a global embargo on diamond exports from Sierra Leone,
where a gems-for-guns trade is financing a civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council plans Wednesday morning to discuss a
draft resolution, initiated by Britain, which would ban all rough
diamonds from Sierra Leone until the government of the West
African nation could set up a proper certification system for the
gems -- as well as regain access to lucrative diamond-mining areas
under the control of the rebel United Revolutionary Front.
</P>
<P>
Central at issue is whether the embargo should run for 18
months as France wants, or 36 months as the United States prefers.
</P>
<P>
Diamonds, gold, iron ore and bauxite accounted for about two
thirds of Sierra Leone's exports before war in the 1990s wrecked
the economy of the West African country. Rebels control some 90
percent of the diamond mines, which yield among the best stones in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
