<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Successfully Launches Military Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia Wednesday successfully
launched a military satellite Cosmos-2371 with a two-stage Proton
booster rocket from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, said
the Russian Strategic Missile Force press service.
</P>
<P>
The rocket fired off from the base at 3:44 a.m. Moscow time (
0044 GMT) and brought the satellite into a geo-stationary orbit at
10:20 a.m. Moscow time (0720 GMT) Wednesday, the press center told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The launch was prepared and actuated by the Russian Aerospace
Agency, and the Strategic Missile Force was responsible for launch-
control and will control its orbiting flight, said the press
center.
</P>
<P>
The satellite has been added to the Russian orbiting system and
raised its efficiency. The launch has demonstrated the quality of
the Proton-K rocket-booster, modernized by the recommendations of
the state commission investigating the Proton crashes in July and
October 1999.
</P>
<P>
The next launch of the modernized Proton-K rocket-booster,
manufactured by the Khrunichev Space Center, is scheduled for July
12. The rocket will send into orbit the Russian "Zvezda" service
module for the planned international space station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
