<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Disappointed at U.S. Court Ruling on Tobacco Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada is disappointed over the U.S.
court ruling released Tuesday to dismiss Ottawa's land-mark
tobacco lawsuit against cigarette smuggling into the country.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Justice Department said Tuesday that the
government is "disappointed with the ruling" and "will review to
determine the best way to redress the injuries that Canada has
suffered."
</P>
<P>
"As in other cases involving rulings on points of law, an
appeal is not out of the question," said Justice Department lawyer
Gordon Bourgard.
</P>
<P>
In a 51-page ruling, a New York district court decided to
accept the defendants' argument that the case is an attempt by the
Canadian government to collect invaded duties and taxes, which is
barred by the U.S. "revenue rule."
</P>
<P>
Canada has spent more than 4 million Canadian dollars (about 2.
7 million U.S. dollars) on legal fees since the country launched
its most high-profile lawsuit against U.S.-based RJ Reynolds
Tobacco Co., five related companies and the Canadian Tobacco
Manufacturers Council last December.
</P>
<P>
The government accused the defendants of smuggling at least two
billion cigarettes into Canada between 1991 and 1994, undermining
the country's goal of protecting young people from smoking by
levying heavy taxes on cigarettes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
