<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Shanghai Five" Nations Pledge Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUSHANBE, Tajikistan, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of the "
Shanghai Five" nations pledged here Wednesday to deepen
cooperation in the fields of politics, foreign affairs, economy
and trade, as well as military affairs to turn Central Asia into a
region of peace, good neighborhood, stability and equal
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of China, Tajikistan, Russia, Kazakhstan and
Kyrgyzstan made the remarks in a joint statement at their one-day
meeting, commonly known as the "Shanghai Five" summit, that has
been held annually since 1996.
</P>
<P>
While expressing their satisfaction with the mutual trust and
cooperation among them, the five nations reaffirmed opposition to
any conflict, threat and external interference that would
complicate the situation in Central Asia, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
They said that their accord on the resolution of border issues
and reinforcement of military trust demonstrated a new concept of
security based on mutual trust, equality and cooperation, which
helps to strengthen mutual understanding and good-neighborhood and
makes constructive contribution to the regional stability.
</P>
<P>
All the five countries would faithfully implement the
agreements signed in Shanghai, China, in 1996 and in Moscow,
Russia, in 1997 on deepening trust in the military field and
cutting down military forces along the border areas, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The five heads of state called for speeding up the process of
strengthening trust in the military field, with measures including
joint military exercises and drilling, exchange of experience in
peacekeeping activities, and relevant seminars and sport
competitions.
</P>
<P>
The five nations agreed that meetings of their defense
ministers and consultations among their defense institutions are
helpful to further strengthening their mutual trust and friendly
cooperation in the military field as well as jointly maintaining
regional peace and stability, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the five nations reiterated that their cooperation
is not directed against any other country and is open to other
countries for participation in concrete programs and projects on a
country-to-country basis or other levels.
</P>
<P>
The top leaders of the five countries started their first
summit in Shanghai, China, in April 1996 to exchange views on
bilateral and multilateral cooperation and other regional and
international issues of common interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
