<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Opposes Austria's Referendum on EU Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- France warned Austria against any act
of "blackmail" on the reform of European institutions on Wednesday,
one day after the Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel announced
to hold a referendum on European Union (EU) sanctions against his
country.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman for the French Foreign Ministry, Anne Gazeau-
Secret, said that France has taken note of the decision by
Schuessel to hold a referendum in October or November if the EU
does not lift its sanctions imposed on Vienna by mid-October.
</P>
<P>
"It would certainly not be in the interests of Austria to
practice such a blackmail", said Gazeau-Secret when asked about a
possible blocking by Austria in the talks on EU institutional
reform.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over the six-month rotating EU presidency
this month, plans to complete by the end of the year the inter-
government negotiations between the 15 EU countries on
institutional reform in order to pave the way for admitting new
members in Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the Austrian far-right Freedom Party, Joerg
Haider, said on Sunday that Austria would block the reform of EU
institutions because of EU sanctions. He had repeatedly threatened
that Austria could consider pulling out of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel apparently yielded to the pressure from Haider by
announcing the holding of a referendum, which will ask the
Austrian population to express its view on the EU sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed sanctions on Vienna in late January after the
Freedom Party entered a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include the suspension of bilateral meetings with
Austrian ministers and refusal to support Austria's candidacy for
international posts.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said on Monday that the EU
sanctions will stay in force until the experts designated by the
European Court of Human Rights submit their report on the
political and human rights situation in Austria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
