<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Government Urges Weapons Stealers to Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government is
appealing to the group of criminals who stole weapons from two
army camps in Gerik in the northern state of Perak on Sunday to
surrender.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to their good sense, if they have any, to surrender
and give up whatever they are doing," Defense Minister Najib Tun
Razak said at a news conference after meeting Deputy Prime
Minister and Home Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On how the government would go about handling the surrender
offer, he said the details would be jointly determined by the
police and the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Najib said that if the offer to surrender themselves is not
taken up the government has the right to take whatever action
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"And there's no limit to that action because the government is
firm in this matter and we don't want this group of robbers and
criminals to achieve their aim," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that no formal contact has been established
with the criminals so far and that they had not made any demands.
However, he added, the government would not give in to demands
made by criminals, if there were any.
</P>
<P>
Najib did not rule out the possibility of ex-servicemen being
involved in the arms heists, saying that from the assessment made,
there was a big possibility that all members of the group are
still together at their hideout on a hillock at the small town of
Sauk in the state.
</P>
<P>
The hideout of the weapon stealers has been tightly cordoned
off by security forces to the extent that there is no possibility
for the criminals to get out from the area, he said, adding "We
have adequate security forces to ensure the cordon was very tight
and was impossible to be penetrated by the group."
</P>
<P>
The minister said a shoot-out took place earlier Wednesday
between the security forces and the group as the criminals wanted
to test the effectiveness of the cordon.
</P>
<P>
In the shoot-out incident Wednesday morning, one of the raiders
was shot by the security forces but the extent of his injuries
could not be ascertained as the group retreated into the jungle
with the injured man.
</P>
<P>
Najib said the presence of three hostages complicated matters
and the government was sensitive to the situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police called for cooperation from the families of
the criminals to help in negotiations between the security forces
and the group.
</P>
<P>
The group of 15 impersonators struck at the two camps in the
state within three hours early Sunday and made off with a haul of
more than 100 rifles and thousands of rounds of ammunition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
