<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Pledges Another 100 Million Euro for Chernobyl Shelter Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Wednesday
pledged another 100 million euro (95 million U.S. dollars) for the
Chernobyl Shelter Fund.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made in Berlin at a conference for funding
rehabilitation of the sarcophagus sheltering reactor 4 of the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
"This very substantial EU effort is fully in line with repeated
expressions of the EU in support of Chernobyl (closure),"  EU
external relations commissioner Christopher Patten said at the
meeting, the second of its kind.
</P>
<P>
The union has so far provided Ukraine with 350 million euro (
332.5 million dollars) in special funds for closing down Chernobyl
plant and Chernobyl-related projects.
</P>
<P>
The commission believes that the potential danger arising from
the damaged unit would persist unless the highly radioactive
material guarded by the existing sarcophagus shelter was
permanently isolated from the environment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Ukraine assured the closure of the last
operating nuclear reactor on December 15 at Chernobyl, the site of
the world's worst ever nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
"The recent decision of President (Leonid) Kuchma and the
Ukrainian government to stick to the commitment made under the
1995 Memorandum of Understanding with the G-7 and to definitely
shut down the last operating reactor at Chernobyl on December 15,
2000 paved the way for continued substantial support by the
international community and the EU," said Patten. 
</P>
</TEXT>
