<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mass Media Urged to Devote More to Reporting Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- An environment reporting project
was launched in Hong Kong Wednesday to encourage the local media
to devote more efforts to reporting environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
"It is with a sense of urgency that we are launching what we
believe is Asia's first university-based program for training
professional and student reporters in environmental journalism,"
Lily Yam, secretary for the environment and food, said when
announcing the project at a conference on environmental journalism
at the University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"By fostering quality environmental journalism, we will help
monitor government actions while keeping the public informed of
its good deeds," Yam said.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll by the university's public opinion program shows
that about half of the Hong Kong residents think the media pay too
little attention to environmental issues. It also shows that
nearly 70 percent of residents think the public has a low level of
awareness about environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Criticism also came from academic studies that have found local
newspapers devoted little efforts to reporting environmental
issues. "Some of the local journalists often ask very stupid or
irrelevant questions on the environment," said Hung Wing-tat,
director of Hong Kong Conservancy Association.
</P>
<P>
He attributed lower financial incentives to reduce air and
water pollution to less devotion given by the mass media to the
issue. "In fact, the mass media are the most useful machines to
promote the initiatives to improve local air and water quality,"
Hung noted.
</P>
<P>
"We depend on the mass media to win support, but we are
disappointed, because TV stations only devote 15 seconds to
environmental reporting every day with no features and analyses,"
Hung added.
</P>
<P>
Other scholars believed that they were quite impressed by some
TV journalists' deep insights into the issues. "The point is that
environmental reporting is intrinsically political," said William
Barron, director of the Center of Urban Planning and Environmental
Management.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of environment is inherently one of politics, and it
ends at the government's decision," Barron said. "We are gratified
that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government has
finally made cleaning up the environment a top policy priority."
</P>
<P>
The panelists of the conference, who have dealt extensively
with the media in their various roles as policymaker, expert and
activist, believed that the new environmental reporting project
will help working journalists across the region acquire the tools,
information and training they need to produce quality
environmental reporting.
</P>
<P>
According to the Journalism and Media Studies Center, under the
project, seminars, workshops and short courses will be held in the
coming years for working journalists and interested parties in
Hong Kong, China's mainland and the Asia Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
As one key ingredient of the project, a website designed
especially for reporters working on environment-related stories
was unveiled at the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Sets Up China's Largest Electronics Training Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China's largest training base for
professionals of the optical electronics and information
industries was officially founded today in this capital of central
China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The newly-established Optical Electronics and Information
Institute of the Central China Science and Technology University
boasts over 1,000 professors and assistant professors.
</P>
<P>
Members of the institute's board include the university, the
Wuhan Office of the Optical Electronics Industrial Base, the Wuhan
Institute of Posts and Telecommunications and a research center
under the China Shipping Industry Group, all heavyweights in the
field of optical electronics.
</P>
<P>
The founding of the institute is expected to give a further
impetus to the city's ambitious plan to build China's largest
optical electronics information base, which will raise its output
value to 100 billion yuan by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The institute expects to eventually turn out over 500
university graduates, 300 post-graduates and 80 Ph.Ds each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
