<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Process With MILF to Continue: Govt Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government maintains
open lines of communication with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) in its desire to secure a just and enduring peace in
Mindanao, a senior official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary Ricardo Puno, who is also presidential
spokesman, said in a statement that the MILF has already declared
its willingness to work with the government peace panel in
hammering out a "comprehensive and peaceful resolution to the
Mindanao situation despite the ongoing conflict."
</P>
<P>
"Consultations are currently being conducted by the MILF with
their political leaders and commanders on the political package
offered by the government as contained in House Bill No. 7883,"
Puno said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The results of the MILF's consultation shall be presented
during the July 29, 2000 meeting of the government and the MILF
peace panels, Puno noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Puno, House Bill No. 7883 pertains to the measure
expanding the coverage of the existing Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM) to include other provinces and cities in the
island.
</P>
<P>
This amended act will still have to undergo a plebiscite to
secure the approval of the people covered by the expanded ARMM, in
accordance with the provisions of the Constitution, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Puno stressed the two conditions set by President
Joseph Estrada -- for the MILF to give up its bid for an
independent Islamic state and to stop its terrorist and criminal
acts -- "must be satisfied for the peace talks to progress."
</P>
<P>
Puno also made it clear that the continued military operations
against the MILF in Mindanao is a legitimate act by the government
to "protect its citizenry, uphold the law and defend the
Constitution."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the military confirmed that starting from Saturday
evening, the government troopers launched an air attack at the
Camp Abubakar, the MILF's headquarters in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
This was the first ever wave of military offensive against the
MILF's biggest camp, that was staged following the June 30
deadline set by President Estrada.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reportedly failed to sign an interim peace accord
before the end of the government-set deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
