<HEADLINE> Knesset Lifts Mordechai's Immunity to Allow Indictment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament) House
Committee on Wednesday removed former Transport Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai's immunity so that he can stand trial on criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen members of the committee voted in favor of lifting
Mordechai's immunity while Roni Milo from Mordechai's Center Party
abstained.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting, Mordechai made his comment in the Knesset on
the attorney general's decision to indict him on sexual harassment
charges.
</P>
<P>
"From the beginning of the affair, an unprecedented and
unbridled crusade of abuse and instigation was held against me," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I was indicted, convicted and punished without a trial ... all
I have to say in my defense -- and I have a lot to say -- I will
say in court," He added.
</P>
<P>
"In the present circumstances I request my immunity to be
lifted, so that trial can be held," Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
The case against Mordechai came as a result of a complaint by a
Transport Ministry female staffer in March that Mordechai sexually
harassed and assaulted her. Two other women also came up to accuse
Mordechai of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai resigned from his post as transport minister and from
the Center Party leadership in May following the announcement of
plans by Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein to arraign him.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein detailed on Wednesday to the committee the main
charges against Mordechai and asked the committee to lift
Mordechai's immunity, allowing him to face trial.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the lifting of Mordechai's immunity, an indictment
will be submitted to the Jerusalem magistrate's court. The trial
may go on for many months as Mordechai denies the accusations
against him and the prosecution wants to bring 39 witnesses to the
stand.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses include head of the police investigation
department and the three women who made the complaints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
