<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Fears New Demarcation Map in Israel's Favor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon fears that a new map drawn by
a United Nations team over the verification of Israel's withdrawal
from south Lebanon will be in Israel's favor and at Lebanon's
expense.
</P>
<P>
The "blue line" map, which was submitted to the Security Council
on Monday night, will be presented to the Israeli government on
Thursday and the Lebanese government on Friday by U.N. Middle East
envoy Terje Roed Larsen and chief U.N. cartographer Miklos Pinther
during their upcoming trip to the region, An Nahar newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
The new map raised fears among Lebanese officials that certain
adjustments would be introduced on the withdrawal line to exonerate
Israel's current border encroachments, An Nahar said.
</P>
<P>
Some local newspapers said Israeli pressure was behind the
projected introduction of the new line that involved three major
changes from the original "blue line" map, drawn last month by
Larsen and Pinther to measure the compatibility of Israel's
withdrawal with U.N. resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is determined to reject the new line, which includes
some changes on the border, and insist on the "original demarcation
that was based on the 1923 internationally recognized border line
with Israel," officials said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Pinther "has drawn a new line that removes
all Israeli trespasses" while the chief cartographer said he used
82 maps from the archives of the U.N., Britain and France to draw
the new map.
</P>
<P>
Safir newspaper said the main objective of Larsen and Pinther in
the upcoming trip is to bring about a consensus between Lebanon and
Israel on the demarcation. "He also carries an urgent U.N. request
for Lebanon to permit the deployment of U.N. peacekeeping force
(UNIFIL) in liberated south Lebanon before the end of July," the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL, which had verified the border with Lebanese authorities,
acknowledged the existence of 12 Israeli encroachments on Lebanese
land in its latest report to the Security Council on Sunday, which
supports Lebanon's official accusation of border violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
