<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates has emerged as the largest
producer of condensates in the Middle East, followed by Saudi
Arabia, local newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
"We expect condensate output from Adnoc-operated projects to
reach 400,000 barrels per day (bdp) this year, compared with 300,
000 bdp by Saudi Aramco," an oil trader was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The trader added that with ongoing works by the Abu Dhabi Co for
Onshore Oil Operations, Abu Dhabi Marine Operating Co and the Abu
Dhabi Liquefied Gas Co, the UAE is expected to increase production
further over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt led Arab countries in the number of oil and
natural gas discoveries last year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt made 19 discoveries in 1999, accounting for 42 percent of
the total made by the 10-member Organization of Arab Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OAPEC), a English-language newspaper quoted
the OAPEC annual report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The organization called on the Egyptian government to continue
widening the scope of prospecting activities in Northern Sinai, the
Red Sea, the Nile Valley and Delta, and the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt Telecom is planning to cut prices by 25 percent
for telephone calls to a number of foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Okail Hamed Basher, newly appointed chairman of the company,
said on Tuesday that a working team has been formed to specify the
prices for various services offered, including international calls
and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
Basher, meanwhile, denied any imminent cut of the prices for
domestic and mobile phone calls. But he said the issue needs to be
studied.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish State Planning Organization (DPT) gave green
light to 16 out of 29 power projects with a total 1,034 megawatt
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The projects, which are planned to be launched by 2002, also
include natural gas, hydroelectric, wind plants.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the reason why the 16 projects were chosen
was because their financing was in order and ready to go.
</P>
<P>
They indicated that many of the projects waiting for approval by
the Energy and Natural Resources Ministry were not supported by the
Treasury because it can only guarantee a limited amount of funds.
The DPT does not support them because it believes that excess
capacity will emerge in the energy sector in the coming years.
</P>
</TEXT>
