<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Large Scale Fabric Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka on Wednesday launched a
large scale fabric project which is the single largest investment
in the industrial sector approved so far for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Board of Investment Thilan Wijesinghe said the
project worth 3 billion rupees (38 million U.S. dollars) is a
joint venture between a local company and a British company to
manufacture weft knitted fabric.
</P>
<P>
MAS Holdings (Pvt) Ltd. will share the equity investment with
Textured Jersey Ltd. of Britain on an equal basis to set up the
joint venture at the Sitawaka Industrial Zone, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
Textured Jersey will provide the state-of-the-art technical
expertise while MAS will provide the personnel and professional
and operational management.
</P>
<P>
The venture, the first to manufacture weft knitted fabric in
Sri Lanka, will provide 23 percent of the fabric that Sri Lankan
garment manufacturers require after being put into production in
July next year.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka annually imports 41 million square meters of weft
knitted fabric at the cost of 123 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Garments are Sri Lanka's major export item. However, the
country has to import most of the fabrics which are used to
manufacture garments because domestically made fabrics are scarce
here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
