<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Expects World's 1st Bottlenose Dolphin by Artificial Insemination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is expecting the birth
of the world's first baby bottlenose dolphin by artificial
insemination in May 2001, researchers at Hong Kong Ocean Park said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Project leader Fiona Brook of the Hong Kong Polytechnic
University and his colleagues at the Ocean Park confirmed the park
's unprecedented success in producing the pregnancy by artificial
insemination of a bottlenose dolphin.
</P>
<P>
The new mother-to-be "Ada" is among four female dolphins chosen
to receive artificial insemination in April this year, but the
other three's pregnancy has not been confirmed yet, Brook said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an exciting breakthrough for the care and
understanding of marine mammals," said Brook. "We have been able
to study and learn so much more about dolphins here and that
knowledge will help to ensure the health and well-being of
dolphins in captivity worldwide," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, Ocean Park and the Hong Kong Polytechnic
University began a collaborative research program to investigate
the reproductive physiology of dolphins and ways to control
breeding with the aim of maximizing their genetic health.
</P>
<P>
The program, acknowledged as being at the forefront of marine
mammal care and breeding science, has since attracted attention
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Researchers are now able to access the maturity of each dolphin
and identify and monitor ovarian cycles in female dolphins, which
makes it possible for them to artificially create dolphin
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
"There are many advantages of artificial insemination," added
Ocean Park's Chief veterinarian, Natalie Rourke, suggesting the
project's scientific significance. "It means that there may be no
need to take more dolphins from the wild; there will be less risk
and disruption to the animals; new genes can be introduced into
isolated groups of animals and it may be possible to enhance
reproduction in endangered species."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
