<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Test-Fires Surface-to-Air Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday successfully test-
fired a home-made multi-target surface-to-air missile, Akash, from
the Interim Test Range at Chandipur in the eastern coastal state
of Orissa, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The 650-kilogram sleek missile was fired from a missile
launcher at around 11:30 a.m. Wednesday and all data concerning
various parameters of the test were being analyzed, the PTI quoted
test range sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
With a range of 25 kilometers, Akash could deliver 55 kilograms
of both conventional and nuclear explosives, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
The missile, a part of India's guided missile development
program started in 1983, uses the integrated two-stage Ramjet
propulsion technology and has the capacity to strike several
targets simultaneously, the PTI added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0165 </DOCNO>
