<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Size Down Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian army is to reduce its
size by 4, 000 annually, according to the country's Chief of Army
Staff General Vitor Malu.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian press Wednesday quoted him as saying that the
downsizing of the 84,000 strong army was in line with the vision
of the present administration to have a more compact, mobile and
effective troop.
</P>
<P>
He said here on Tuesday that about 5,000 soldiers would be
disengaged from the force before the end of the year while 1,000
would be recruited to bring the "net attrition rate" to 4,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
Malu also confirmed that some of the officers accused of
wrongdoings under former military regimes have been sacked from
the service.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian army's main goal is to keep the "oneness" of Nigeria,
which is currently under threat of ethnic clashes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The army would no longer allow itself to be cajoled into
politics, he said, as "the present generation of the military is
quite aware that our orders come from the political class."
</P>
<P>
The armed forces ruled the country in more than half of the
years after it gained its independence in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
