<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, U.S. Kick Off Naval Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONBURI, THAILAND, July 5 (Xinhua)-- Thailand and the United
States started a bilateral naval exercise Wednesday in the waters
along the coast of Chonburi Province, 94 kilometers east of
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
"This year's exercise is intended to ensure that our forces are
prepared to work together to meet real world challenges," U.S.
Ambassador to Thailand Richard E. Hecklinger said at the opening
ceremony of the exercise, which is held at the Sattahip Naval Base
of Chonburi Province.
</P>
<P>
The exercise is the second phase of a series of bilateral naval
exercises conducted annually by the U.S. Navy with several
countries in Southeast Asia, under the code-name of CARAT (
Cooperation Afloat Readiness And Training).
</P>
<P>
This year, the first phase of the CARAT began in the
Philippines on June 14 and the final phase will be carried out in
Singapore on September 22, according to Hecklinger.
</P>
<P>
"The exercise offers excellent opportunities for both U.S. and
Thai personnel to exchange knowledge, improve skills and
efficiency in many areas," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Thai exercise, which will last till July 14, includes
operation planning, shipboard operations, special warfare, weapons
training, humanitarian operations and public affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The ultimate objective is to strengthen the good relation and
enhance inter-operability between Thai and U.S. personnel," the
ambassador noted.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,800 U.S. soldiers, sailors, pilots and marines are
participating in the games with some 4,400 Thai military personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
