<HEADLINE> Weapon Stealer Wounded in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Security forces Wednesday shot
and wounded a man during a brief skirmish with a group of weapon
stealers who are surrounded on a hillock in Sauk in Malaysia's
northern state of Perak, police said.
</P>
<P>
The extent of the man's injury could not be ascertained as his
fellow members dragged him away, Inspector-General of Police
Norian Mai told reporters at a police station near Sauk, Bernama
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of fire occurred Wednesday morning at the Bukit
Jenalek jungle, he said, adding that during the exchange, the
group fired three shots first and when the security forces
returned fire, a shot hit one of the gang members.
</P>
<P>
The police chief said the gang could be politically motivated
and its members are part of a mystical cult.
</P>
<P>
Norian also confirmed that the group is still holding three
people hostage, including two policemen.
</P>
<P>
The group of 15 impersonators raided two army camps in the
state within three hours early Sunday and made off with a haul of
more than 100 rifles and thousands of rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
Sauk town is the center of a massive combined police-military
operations against the group, who are trapped on the hillock.
</P>
</TEXT>
