<HEADLINE> More Bombs Found in Indonesian Attorney General's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Following a bomb blast at the
Indonesian Attorney General's Office (AGO) Tuesday afternoon, a
cardboard box containing two bombs was reportedly found again by
the police in a toilet on the third floor of the AGO Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But police told reporters that the bombs had been defused by
bomb specialists of the National Police (Polri) in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police are still investigating the origin of the
bombs. There are also no reports about whether the new bombs have
anything to do with the one which exploded in the AGO the day
before.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a bomb explosion rocked the AGO, just hours after
the youngest son of former President Soeharto underwent
questioning in connection with corruption charges. No casualties
were reported in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Polri Gen. Rusdihardjo said Wednesday that the
police still do not know whether any links existed between Tuesday
's explosion and the questioning of Soeharto's son, Tommy.
</P>
<P>
"We still don't know whether there is a link between the blast
and Tommy's questioning," Rusdihardjo said.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Attorney General Marzuki Darusman said he will not
be afraid of confronting such bomb terror.
</P>
<P>
"We will not be afraid," Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
He said his office's work pace would not slacken following
Tuesday's bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, we are determined to work as one man to
complete the cases we are handling," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
