<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Stresses Developing Arab Ties With Turkey, Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has stressed the importance for
Arab countries to develop ties with both Turkey and Iran, two
Muslim heavyweights in the Middle East, the Egyptian Gazette
newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the first annual meeting of the non-governmental
Egyptian Council for Foreign Affairs, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
on Tuesday called for proper handling of strains, if any, between
the Arab world and the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We can not think of the future of peace in the Middle East
without taking into consideration the Arab world's relations with
Turkey and Iran," Moussa told the audience.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Council for Foreign Affairs, set up in June 1999,
is an independent think tank on regional and international issues
which groups former diplomats, military commanders, businessmen and
intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
"The international political environment is still in a state of
flux and the future of the Middle East will be greatly affected by
the changes taking place in this amorphous system," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized Egypt's keenness on maintaining good relations
with Ankara, saying that Turkey plays a key role in the Mideast
political and economic arena.
</P>
<P>
A predominantly Muslim but politically secular nation, Turkey
has become a regional ally of Israel. The Arabs were dubious of
their relations with Turkey, although it claimed that its
cooperation with Israel is not aimed against any third party and it
attaches importance to ties with Arab and Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also said that progress has been achieved in improving
Cairo-Tehran ties, adding that positive steps are being taken
toward a normalization of relations.
</P>
<P>
Tehran cut off diplomatic ties with Cairo in 1979 after Egypt
signed a peace agreement with Israel, which it refused to recognize
but viewed as its arch-enemy. The two sides, nevertheless, have
come closer in the past few years due to joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said last Sunday that Egypt and Iran have held high-level
talks aimed at normalizing the ties, which "are making progress."
</P>
<P>
The talks followed a telephone conversation June 21 between
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and his Iranian counterpart
Mohammad Khatami, the first direct contact between leaders of the
two countries in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office nearly three years ago, Khatami, a moderate,
has been advocating a policy of detente, instead of the previous
policy of exporting Islamic revolution. This change enabled Iran's
Arab neighbors, especially the Gulf states, to seek warmer
relations with it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Relieved over U.S. Backing for Iraqi Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey was reassured that the Iraqi
opposition groups, which are trying to topple President Saddam
Hussein, got "no concrete" support from the U.S. government after
week-long talks, analysts here said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi oppositions had asked for anti-tank weapons to be used
against Saddam's army, but the request was rejected by Washington,
unwilling to see conflicts in northern Iraq escalating, Turkish
Daily News reported.
</P>
<P>
The United States only agreed to train up to 145 members of the
Iraqi oppositions-in-exile for an unarmed struggle in the fields of
medicine, logistics, computer, communications, broadcasting and
power generation.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meetings, Turkey expressed concerned over a revival
of the U.S. ambitious plan to overthrow the Saddam regime as the U.
S. presidential race gears up.
</P>
<P>
Turkey prefers a stable Iraq with territorial integrity to
getting rid of Saddam, which could cause serious consequences,
including a possible Kurdish state in northern Iraq bordering
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
This is because Ankara loathes to see a spillover of Kurdish
independent movement in northern Iraq into its own restive Kurdish-
populated southeast.
</P>
<P>
Since last year's capture of Abdullah Ocalan, chieftain of the
outlawed Kurdistan workers Party (PKK), Turkey has successfully
suppressed the PKK, which had been fighting for 15 years for self-
rule in southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Turkey would not permit the founding of an
independent Kurdish state in the region, urging Baghdad to
reinforce control over its Kurdish-populated area.
</P>
<P>
Ankara is now considering upgrading diplomatic representation to
ambassadorial level in a bid to improve bilateral relations and
join efforts to check the separatist movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Govt Expands Partnership With Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen
chaired a public forum here Wednesday to hear concerns raised by
the private sector about its investment difficulties in this
country.
</P>
<P>
"I gave instructions to increase the time of our meeting ... so
that all investors and business people will be able and have
enough time to discuss and air their grievances and concerns
pertaining to the general investment and business environment in
Cambodia," Hun Sen said in an opening speech to about 200 forum
participants.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the government's strategic motto is "poverty
reduction through high economic growth over the long term by
ensuring environmental sustainability and social equity."
</P>
<P>
Security and corruption are among the biggest concerns raised
by the private sector about investing in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"I am never tired of repeating that Cambodia enjoys today
unprecedented favorable conditions conducive to development never
seen during the last few decades," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said his government has been committed to
one-stop service since last year, which paves the way for
investors to get approval within a period of 28 days.
</P>
<P>
The government-private sector forum is held twice a year
starting from last December.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, meanwhile, said his government should strengthen the
government-private sector structure by setting up joint sectoral
working groups, such as those on legal affairs and regulatory
measures,tax policy, banking and finance, processing and garment
industry.
</P>
<P>
So far, the garment industry gets the most investment in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
There were just 70 garment factories in 1997 and 120 in 1998
and now the number has increased to 178. Many are owned by
companies based in South Korea, China's Hong Kong, Malaysia and
Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
