<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Non-Oil/Gas Exports to Reach US$44 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The value of Indonesia's non-oil
and gas exports in the current year is expected to reach 44
billion U.S. dollars or significantly up from last year's 38
billion dollars, a senior official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the value of our non-oil and gas export within
this year will reach 44 billion U.S. dollars or up from last year'
s figure of 38 billion U.S. dollars," Minister of Trade and
Industry, Luhut Binsar Panjaitan, said at a hearing of the House
of Representatives Commission V on trade and industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will hammer out a plan to meet the
target. "And if we are able to reach such targets, we think we
will also be able to provide huge job opportunities," the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that Indonesia is still facing trouble in
enhancing its industrial capacities due to lack of investment.
</P>
<P>
"This condition (lack of investment) has something to do with
the current security condition in the country where riots are
still taking place in some areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, data released by the National Bureau of Statistics (
BPS) showed that the country's non-oil and gas exports dropped by
3.99 percent in May this year to 3.8 billion dollars against 3.9
billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
A decline of 2.94 percent was also recorded in May in total
exports, which amounted to 4.8 billion dollars, compared with 4.9
billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
But the trade surplus in May this year rose by 18 percent to 2.
47 billion dollars from 2.1 billion dollars in the same period
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
