<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Operation to Round Up Army Deserters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched an
islandwide operation to round up thousands of army deserters who
failed to report back during the latest period of amnesty which
expired on June 20, the state radio said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
About 18,000 soldiers of active service have deserted their
ranks during the last few years, the radio said, adding that most
of the army deserters are directly or indirectly responsible for
the recent wave of crime.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense has requested the public to provide
information about army deserters to their respective police
stations.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of army deserters will encourage efforts of crime
prevention, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
It added that those who hide information regarding army
deserters will be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
The 118,000-strong army, plagued by desertions, needs more
soldiers to fight Tamil Tiger rebels, who have been waging a war
to carve out a homeland called Eelam for the minority Tamils in
Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
During the past few months, the government has announced
amnesty three times, but only 5,000 deserters have returned to the
barracks, the military said. At least 30 soldiers desert each
month, a senior official said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
