<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Troops Complete Withdrawal From Kisangani, Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda People's Defence Forces
(UPDF) has completed withdrawal from the city of Kisangani in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) after repeated clashes with
Rwandan army, Ugandan Army Spokesman Phinehas Katirima confirmed
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Katirima told Xinhua: "The Ugandan troops are moving to Buta,
some 300 kilometers away from the northeast Congolese city of
Kisangani."  The last Ugandan soldier in Kisangani arrived at
Banalia, 128 kilometers north of the war-torn city, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council demanded both Rwanda and Uganda to
withdraw their troops from Kisangani after the two armies shelled
each other in early June.
</P>
<P>
Leonida Grecu, officer of U.N. Observer team in Congo (MONUC)
overseeing the withdrawal, said he was happy with the Ugandans'
pullout, according to a New Vision daily report.
</P>
<P>
"The roads are bad but the Ugandans are now far from the 100
kilometers mark. This is a victory for the U.N. mission here,"
Grecu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that Rwandan soldiers had also withdrawn from
Kisangani, but "a few were still at 75 kilometers on
Kisangani-Lubutu road. They are moving with another MONUC team
following them."
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops began implementing an agreement to
demilitarize Kisangani in the wake of clashes in early May.
</P>
<P>
The two former allies have sent their troops to DRC to support
rival rebel factions fighting against the DRC President Laurent
Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Government not to Interfere in Maize Price: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will not
interfere in maize price although some farmers of the country are
complaining of low price offered by what they call greedy buyers,
according to a senior government official.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Wednesday quoted Deputy Agriculture Minister
Enock Chikamba as saying here on Tuesday that the peasant farmers
who are being exploited by greedy maize buyers should not expect
the government to fix the price because it has created a
liberalized environment for them.
</P>
<P>
He said the farmers are to blame for their exploitation by
unscrupulous buyers who have been buying a 90-kg bag of maize at
about 5,000 Kwacha (1.7 U.S. dollars) instead of the commercial
price of 29,000 Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
If they are selling maize they have suffered for at a given
away price then they have only themselves to blame, he said.
</P>
<P>
Considering the country's liberalized economy, the government
can only facilitate the sale of products when it is necessary, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister made the statement in a reaction to
allegations by some peasant farmers that they are exploited by the
maize buyers because the government does not have a proper
agriculture policy.
</P>
<P>
President Frederick Chiluba condemned the exploitation of
farmers by maize buyers last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Sugar Export Quota to EU Rises to 12,000 Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's export quota for
sugar to the European Union countries has increased by 2,000 tons
to reach 12,000 tons in this financial year, the Guardian
newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister for Finance Crispin Hauli was quoted as saying
in the parliament in the central town of Dodoma on Tuesday that
Tanzania obtained the additional 2,000 tons of sugar to the EU
market for the year 2000/2001 after Uganda decided to stop
exporting sugar to EU market.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1975 Lome Convention between the EU and
African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries, Tanzania is
allowed to export 10,000 tons of sugar to the EU market at special
rates annually.
</P>
<P>
"Failure of some ACP countries to export sugar to the EU in
accordance with their quotas accounts for the surplus export of
sugar for Tanzania," explained Hauli, who is also Tanzanian
Ambassador to the EU in Brussels, Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Russia Pledge to Strengthen Cooperation in World Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUSHANBE, Tajikistan, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China and Russia
agreed here on Wednesday to further strengthen their mutual
support and cooperation, and unite other countries to play a
greater role in world affairs.
</P>
<P>
The consensus was reached during a meeting between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Russian President Vladimir Putin, both
here attending the annual summit of the "Shanghai Five" nations,
which also brings together the heads of state from Tajikistan,
Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was the first face-to-face encounter between the
two presidents since Putin took office in May this year, though
they have had several telephone conversations over the past
several months.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Jiang said both the fundamental interest of
the two countries and the special duties the two countries bear
for the world demand that China and Russia strengthen and deepen
the Sino-Russian strategic partnership of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In today's world, China and Russia can play an even greater
role in opposing hegemony and power politics, and push forward the
process of multi-polarization of the world, so long as the two
countries support each other, cooperate closely with each other
and unite other countries of the world in their efforts to this
effect, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president also expressed his appreciation of
Russia's principled stance on the Anti-Ballistic Missiles Treaty,
and said that China and Russia should continue to strengthen and
deepen their cooperation in this field in a joint effort to
maintain the strategic security and stability of the world.
</P>
<P>
On the "Shanghai Five" mechanism, Jiang said that in the past
four year since the establishment of the mechanism, mutual
understanding and trust among the five nations had been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
With the further development of the "Shanghai Five" process,
China and Russia can do even more for safeguarding and promoting
regional peace and stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin agreed with Jiang and said that Russia and China should
further strengthen their cooperation within the "Shanghai Five"
framework, which is playing a more and more important role in
world affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kyrgyzstan Vow to Fight Separatism, Terrorism, Extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUSHANBE, Tajikistan, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China and Kyrgyzstan
vowed here on Wednesday to beef up their joint efforts and
cooperation on fighting separatism, terrorism and extremism, which
are menacing peace and stability of the region and the world.
</P>
<P>
The two countries made the pledge during a meeting between
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Kyrgyzstan President Askar
Akayev, who are here for the annual summit meeting of the "
Shanghai Five" nations.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Jiang said that since China and
Kyrgyzstan share a common position on fighting separatism,
terrorism and extremism, the two countries should continue to
support each other and cooperate with each other more closely to
this effect.
</P>
<P>
He said that China fully supports Akayev's proposal for
establishing an international anti-terrorism center within the
framework of the "Shanghai Five" summit.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the center is not only in the fundamental
interests of the two countries, but also is conducive to
maintaining peace and stability of the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Akayev expressed his gratitude to China for firmly supporting
Kyrgyzstan's efforts to crack down on terrorist activities and
Kyrgyzstan's proposal of setting up the international anti-
terrorism center.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the signing of a border pact among Kyrgyzstan,
China, and Tajikistan on Wednesday was an important event in the
region. Agreeing with him, Jiang said that the signing of the pact
reflected the firm determination of the three countries to
strengthen their good-neighborly friendship and cooperation.
</P>
