<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-share Market Edges Up at Wednesday Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market index
rose 0.48 points or 0.87 percent to 55.54 points at Wednesday's
close.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 12.30 million U.S. dollars, 73.73
percent more than Tuesday's total.
</P>
<P>
Trading was still not very active, but the market did stabilize
late in the session as some positive reports provided a bit more
momentum to thoughts of speeding up reforms of China's stock
market as the country prepares to join the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage foreign-invested companies to list on its
domestic bourses, the domestic media quoted the assistant foreign
trade minister Ma Xiuhong as saying yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Qualified candidates can seek listing either on the yuan-
denominated A-share market or the foreign currency B-share market,
the first official confirmation since British consumer goods maker
Uniliver Plc filed its application for a listing on China's A-
share market last Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported today that China's securities regulator is
considering a proposal to let companies that have listed their
stocks as H shares in Hong Kong sell yuan-denominated A shares in
the country. The China Securities Regulatory Commission may pick
some H-share companies as "test cases" to conduct the experiment.
</P>
<P>
However, the market seemed to have rather muted reaction,
insisting that earnings profile is still the most important factor
in determining the near-term direction.
</P>
<P>
Advancing shares oupaced declining issues by 37 to 11, with six
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Jinqiao Export rose 5.23 percent to 0.322 US dollars, while ST
Steel Tube added 5.08 percent to 0.124 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
New Asia lost 4.20 percent to 0.274 US dollars, while Shangling
fell 2.06 percent to 0.570 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that the market will continue to oscillate,
hovering around the current level, with cautious sentiment
lingering on.  
</P>
