<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Kills 5, Displaces 120,000 in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Five people have died and more than
120,000 others have fled their homes after typhoon Edeng and a
lesser storm,Ditang, slashed through Manila and parts of the
northern Philippines,the government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado, who is also chief of the
National Disaster Coordination Council (NDCC), said that more than
16,000 registered evacuees were staying in four evacuation centers
as of late Tuesday and that the number was rising.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department canceled classes at elementary and
high schools because of flash floods in Metropolitan Manila,
Mercado said,adding that some colleges followed suit as a number
of roads were submerged.
</P>
<P>
Local welfare officials said 120,000 people had abandoned their
homes due to rising floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
The government weather station said typhoon Edeng and a
tropical depression would continue to enhance the southwest
monsoon and bring rains over western sections of the northern
Luzon island, especially Metropolitan Manila.
</P>
<P>
"Residents in the low-lying areas are advised to remain alert
against possible flooding," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon Edeng was packing maximum sustained winds of 150
kilometers per hour and with gusts of up to 185 kilometers per
hour while the tropical depression Ditang had peak sustained winds
of 55 kilometers per hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
