<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Consider Implementing Customs Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) will consider implementing a Customs
Union and the Common External Tariff (CET) after the launch of the
Free Trade Area on October 31, a senior COMESA official has
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary General of the COMESA Sondiso Ngwenya told
Wednesday' s Zambia Daily Mail that COMESA member states have
already committed themselves to the implementation of a CET by the
year 2004 of zero percent, 5 percent, 15 percent and 30 percent on
capital goods, raw materials, intermediate goods and final goods
respectively.
</P>
<P>
He said economic growth can not be addressed by trade policies
alone but through an integrated package of industrial and trade
policies.
</P>
<P>
"These policies must focus on mitigating the impact of factors
that inhibit producers from adjusting and improving productivity,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Pledges Cooperation With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and the United States will
continue to work closely for peace and security in the Horn of
Africa and the Great Lakes region, Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has said.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks Tuesday at a reception marking the 224th
anniversary of American independence at the American ambassador's
residence in Nairobi, media here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Moi expressed satisfaction with the cordial and fruitful
relations enjoyed by the two countries at bilateral and
multilateral levels.
</P>
<P>
The government and people of Kenya were grateful for the
support the U.S. government had extended, especially in
humanitarian and development assistance, Moi said.
</P>
<P>
Moi also thanked the U.S. for generous response towards his
appeal in earlier June for international assistance to supplement
the government's efforts in tackling the effects of the drought.
But he did not mention how much the Americans had donated.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Kenya considered the enactment of the
Africa Growth and Opportunities Act by the U.S. Congress as a
significant step in opening the American market to exports from
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is looking forward to the implementation of this Act and
hopes to see tangible results in the forms of American investment
and substantial increase in trade between the two countries, Moi
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Telecom Union Agrees on New Standards for Voiceband Modems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Telecommunications
Union (ITU) has agreed on three important new standards for
voiceband modems, the ITU announced in a press release received
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Building on the success of the now ubiquitous V.90
Recommendation for modems at data rates up to 56kbit/s, important
enhancements have now been agreed on in new Recommendation ITUT-T
V.92. The enhancements are:
</P>
<P>
-- An increase of more than 40 percent in the maximum data rate
towards the network to a new maximum of 48 kbit/s on the best
connections;
</P>
<P>
-- Significantly quicker start-up times on recognized
connections, and
</P>
<P>
-- The ability to put the modem "on-hold" when the network
indicates that an incoming call is waiting.
</P>
<P>
These enhancements will give significant benefits to the modem
user with improved access to interactive services, and the option
of exploiting voice response facilities associated with Internet
browsing, according to the ITU.
</P>
<P>
The new recommendations were made in Edinburgh, Scotland, last
week at a meeting of the ITU-T Working Party responsible for modem
specifications.
</P>
<P>
These important new features will further improve the Internet
users' experience by significantly reducing connect times and
providing improved access to new Internet services, said an ITU
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
