<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton is expected to announce Wednesday
whether he intends to call for a summit meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Chairman Yasser Arafat, U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who spoke with both Arafat and Barak twice this week,
is leaning toward convening the summit at the end of the month, but
is waiting until after the July 4 (U.S. Independence Day) weekend
to make the announcement.
</P>
<P>
The White House denied reports that July 17 had already been
chosen for the start of the summit, stressing that "there has not
been a decision."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Senior political sources close to Barak said that as long as
prospects exist for progress in talks with the Palestinians and the
Syrians, "there is no point in talking about bringing the Likud
into the government, as that will be interpreted as a toughening of
the Israeli positions."
</P>
<P>
However, the failure of the talks with the Palestinians and the
eruption of violence could lead to the formation of a broad
government with Likud, according to senior sources in both the
opposition right-wing Likud party and the ruling One Israel bloc.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- An expanded panel of 11 Israeli Supreme Court judges will on
Wednesday continue its hearings on whether to recognize non-
Orthodox conversions to Judaism.
</P>
<P>
The last hearing was held on April 11, during which
representatives of the State Attorney's office presented the
Interior Ministry's position.
</P>
<P>
They said that every conversion performed in Israel must have
the approval of the Chief Rabbinate before the would-be convert can
be registered as a Jew on his ID card.
</P>
<P>
Conversions performed abroad will only be recognized (if they do
not have the Chief Rabbinate's approval) if the convert has been
part of the community in which the conversion was carried out for
at least a year, it added.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- A joint panel of members of the Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Law and Internal Affairs committees on Tuesday approved in the
first reading an amendment to the Basic Law: Jerusalem, barring the
government from ceding any part of it or any national or municipal
prerogatives over it to a foreign entity.
</P>
<P>
The initiator of the bill, Yehoshua Matza from Likud, made it
clear that he had in mind the reports of possible custodial or
limited self-government arrangements with the Palestinians in the
framework of a peace treaty, including granting the PNA control of
the Temple Mount or allowing broad autonomy in the Palestinian
neighborhoods of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was sponsored by 80 Knesset members, was
approved on May 17 by a vote of 68 to 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
