<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Parliament Passes Budget for Fiscal 2000-2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali Parliament Wednesday
passed the national budget for fiscal 2000-2001 totaling 92
billion rupees(1.3 billion U.S. dollars) with an overall deficit
of 26.8 billion rupees(374 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Though the ambitious budget, presented to the parliament on May
30, had drawn mixed reactions from the opposition and the public,
it got passed in the parliament by voice vote without much
hindrance.
</P>
<P>
The budget set aside 43.5 billion rupees (603 million dollars)
for regular expenditure, including expenses by the government,
military, police and judiciary, while 48.1 billion rupees (688
million dollars) will be allocated to development projects,
including those related to poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
It aims to raise 64.82 billion rupees (927 million dollars)from
revenue and new tax proposals, besides receiving about 20 billion
rupees (300 million dollars) from bilateral and multilateral
grants.
</P>
<P>
While defending his budget proposal in the parliament, Finance
Minister Mahesh Acharya said the new budget had laid emphasis "on
the reforms of the Nepali economy and accorded high priority to
the agricultural and social sectors in line with the goal of
poverty alleviation," which is the imperative task of the Nepali
government.
</P>
<P>
However, the substantial increase in the salary of government
employees, police, army and teachers proposed in the budget is
feared to enhance inflation, further marginalizing the ordinary
people, about 50 percent of whom are living below the poverty line
(an average daily income of less than 1 U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
Bharat Mohan Adhikary, chief whip of the Communist Party of
Nepal-United Marxist and Leninist (CPN-UML), the leading
opposition party,criticized the budget for "failing to introduce
concrete programs for the agriculture, industry and trade sectors
and to encourage the poor and people of downtrodden communities
for the upliftment of their lives."
</P>
<P>
The new fiscal year is to start on July 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
