<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais to Enjoy Cheaper Mobile Phone Charge Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai people can expect to enjoy
cheaper mobile phone service next year as the government has
approved a new 1900-megahertz cellular phone system with an
investment of 4.2 billion baht (25.6 million U.S. dollars),
Thailand News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet approved the grand project at its weekly meeting on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new mobile phone service will offer a lower monthly fee of
300 baht (7.69 dollars), compared with the 500 baht (12.8 dollars)
fee charge now.
</P>
<P>
The system will be owned and operated by three state agencies
that will set up a new company to run it.
</P>
<P>
The Telephone Organization of Thailand (TOT) will hold 54.98
percent of the new company while the Communications Authority of
Thailand (CAT) and Aeronautical Radio of Thailand will hold 40
percent and 0.02 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
CAT and TOT employees will hold a combined 5-percent stake in
the newly established company.
</P>
<P>
TOT and CAT are preparing to give up their roles as regulators
and providers of telecommunication concessions and to compete with
former concession holders after privatization.
</P>
<P>
The new company will compete with three existing private
cellular phone operators, which operate under concessions from CAT.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled to begin in 13 months with Greater
Bangkok as its first service area. It would be expanded to the
provinces within three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
