<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder:Togo to Host 36th OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) will hold its 36th annual summit of heads of state and
government in the Togolese capital of Lome from July 10 to 12.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming summit will be preceded by the 72nd ordinary
session of the council of ministers on July 6-8, which will make
preparations for the summit.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that African leaders will focus their
discussions mainly on the three themes of regional cooperation and
integration, security and stability, and the challenges of
widespread AIDS and poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss the draft treaty on the establishment of the
African Union and the draft protocol to the treaty setting up the
African Economic Community, as follow-up steps to implement the
decisions to accelerate African integration reached during an
extraordinary summit on September 9, 1999, in Syrte, Libya.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are also expected to discuss ways to end various
conflicts on the continent, particularly in Angola, Burundi, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo and Sierra Leone, and the related
situation of refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, Angola, Namibia and Cape Verde have threatened to
boycott the Lome summit on account of alleged violation by the
Togolese government of the U.N. sanctions against the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by
Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The OAU was founded on May 25, 1963, in the Ethiopian capital
of Addis Ababa and the Charter of the Organization was signed on
that occasion by heads of state and government of 32 independent
African states.
</P>
<P>
Its purposes are to promote the unity and solidarity of the
African states, defend the sovereignty, territorial integrity and
independence of members, coordinate and intensify the cooperation
and efforts to achieve a better life for the people of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The organization is also aimed at eradicating all forms of
colonialism from Africa and promoting international cooperation
having due regard to the Charter of the United Nations and the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Addis Ababa-based OAU, which is composed at present of 53
independent African states except Morocco, held the first summit
in Cairo, Egypt, in 1964 and the 35th summit in Algiers, Algeria,
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Algiers summit, the largest ever gathering with 46 heads of
state and government attending, ended with a declaration calling
for peace and development in the new millennium and reversion of
the growing marginalization of Africa in economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
The past 35 years have seen the African continent fulfil the
historic mission to win national independence and decolonization
under the OAU standard.
</P>
<P>
In recent years the pan-African organization has been playing
an increasingly important role in safeguarding peace and stability
and promoting economic development and integration in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Provides Loans to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The French Development Agency has
granted Kenya a credit of 15 million euros (14.23 million U.S.
dollars) to help restore El Nino-devastated infrastructure, the
Kenya Times daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo said Tuesday that the loan
would be utilized for general overhaul and rehabilitation of
roads, water and sanitation facilities in the capital Nairobi and
other districts.
</P>
<P>
The terms of the loan are highly concessionary with the
interest rate of about 2.3 percent per year over a duration of 25
years with a grace period of eight years, Okemo said.
</P>
<P>
The minister estimated the cost of the El Nino related damages
at 48 billion shillings (about 650 million U.S. dollars), saying
the restoration and development of physical infrastructure will be
a primary objective during this fiscal year (July 2000-June 2001).
 
</P>
