<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sci-Tech Museum to Draw More Students in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- In order to attract more students,
China's only national science and technology museum will extend
its opening time from mid-July until October.
</P>
<P>
During the summer holidays from July 15 to August 31, the newly-
enlarged China Sci-Tech Museum located in northern Beijing will
open every day, with visitors having two more hours over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The new exhibition hall of the museum made its debut at the end
of April, and crowds of science enthusiasts have visited the
museum since then.
</P>
<P>
Inside the new exhibition hall are displayed more than 300
items in the fields of space, energy, communications, new
materials, information, life and environmental sciences, as well
as 250 examples of China's ancient sci-tech achievements.
</P>
<P>
The "No Touching" signs which once were common in China's
museums have vanished from the new hall, so that patrons can have
a truly hands-on experience, from space-walking to virtual
football.
</P>
<P>
The Sci-Tech Museum was built in the 1980s under the direction
of late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping. About 700,000 Chinese,
mainly school children, visit the museum every year. The new
facility is expected to greet 1.5 million visitors annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
