<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Mining Industry in New Zealand Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior New Zealand scientist
has called for the development of the mining industry in the
country, saying a more vibrant mining industry would create
thousands of new jobs in regions of high unemployment and inject
an extra 1 billion NZ dollars (about 470 million U.S. dollars)
into the economy.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the fact that New Zealand is a high consumer of
minerals and mineral-based products, New Zealanders appear
increasingly unenthusiastic about doing their global bit to supply
minerals, said Andrew West, chief executive of the Institute of
Geological and Nuclear Sciences Ltd. (GNS) in the July issue of
the company newsletter, Globe.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand seems to have adopted an import approach to the
whole industry because of strict environmental standards that
apply in the country, he said in the issue, which came out here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"For the minerals sector, the equivalent is to allow rational
access to minerals outside of the national parks while maintaining
strict standards for low-environmental impact harvesting and
sophisticated rehabilitation," West said.
</P>
<P>
Intelligent use of natural resources should be an important
part of moves to stimulate regional growth, especially economic
growth in regions of high unemployment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minerals sector has the potential to grow from 12,000 to 20,
000 regional jobs and from 1 billion to 2 billion NZ dollars (from
470 million to 940 million U.S. dollars) in annual turnover, West
estimated.
</P>
<P>
GNS conservatively estimates that New Zealand has at least 86
billion NZ dollars (40.4 billion U.S. dollars) worth of metallic
mineral resources in known and undiscovered deposits, he said,
adding that some of New Zealand's non-metallic minerals are
valuable,niche materials such as zeolite, perlite and diatomite.
</P>
<P>
"They can earn valuable export revenue and some can be used as
the base for developing innovative materials such as sophisticated
ceramics," the scientist said.
</P>
<P>
He concluded by saying the minerals sector "has a lot to offer
New Zealanders. Local, regional and central government should help
unlock its social and economic contribution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
