<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Army to Withdrawal from Chittagong Hill Tracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Army, now deployed to
guard borders of Chittagong Hill Tracts and maintain internal
peace, will be withdrawn from the region and the duty will be
vested in Bangladesh Rifles (BDR), which is ill-equipped and short
of personnel.
</P>
<P>
The New Nation Wednesday quoted a report by Sector Commanders
of BDR as saying that the BDR would immediately need some 5,000
additional personnel backed by at least half a dozen helicopters
to keep mobility in this mineral-rich rugged one-tenth part of
Bangladesh. Without such support security and sovereignty of the
region will remain vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
Besides, some 500 kilometer-long border with India in the
region is unguarded as there are no border outposts there, it
added. The BDR would need another 13,000 personnel to guard it,
because, both Indian militants and their pursuers, the Indian
Border Security Force and Indian army, often enter the area
unobstructed.
</P>
<P>
If Bangladesh has to establish sovereignty on this chunk of
land, action has to be taken now or else, situation could go out
of control, the commanders said in their report, adding the
current transition period which began after the signing of the
Chittagong peace accord on December 2, 1997, would be completed
when the army is to be withdrawn to the cantonments of Chittagong
within next six months.
</P>
<P>
For nearly two decades, there were violence and conflict in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts region. The present government had solved
the long-prevalent crisis after signing a peace accord with the
tribal population in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Defense analysts have maintained that the borders of Bangladesh
with the north eastern India and Myanmar remain sensitive. The
borders of fragile north eastern India in future will be more
unstable as movement in the Indian area for greater self-rule
gains momentum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
