<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Official Media Call for Dissolution of NLD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The official newspaper The New Light
of Myanmar Wednesday called for dissolution and outlawing of the
National League for Democracy (NLD), a winning political party in
the 1990 General Election held by the present military government
under a free and fair basis.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper noted in an unsigned article that the NLD is
harming the non-disintegration of the union, non-disintegration of
the national solidarity and perpetuation of sovereignty -- the
three main causes laid down by the government.
</P>
<P>
It also charged the NLD with constantly committing acts that
bring great disservice to Myanmar, calling it a defunct political
party.
</P>
<P>
The NLD, which was formed and registered in late 1988 after the
military took over the state power on September 18 that year in
the height of the country's political crisis, participated along
with 92 other political parties in the general election held in
May 1990.
</P>
<P>
It then won 396 or 82 percent of the 485 parliamentary seats in
the election.
</P>
<P>
The article said the NLD won the election because the public
was tired of the situation and thus voted for NLD for a change.
</P>
<P>
The article went on to accuse Aung San Suu Kyi, NLD general
secretary, of playing a major role in attempts to top the
government by trying to destroy the Tatmadaw (armed forces).
</P>
<P>
Charging Aung San Suu Kyi with associating with crooked
politicians and accepting outside assistance, it said she seeks
destruction of the nation from outside.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, the NLD demanded the government to implement the
result of the 1990 general election, but was ignored.
</P>
<P>
On September 16, 1998, it unilaterally set up a Committee
Representing the People's Parliament (CRPP) Elected in the 1990
General Election to work for the convening of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
It also charged the government with applying various means to
stop and disturb the emergence of a people's parliament, warning
the country would continue to be in the crisis in politics,
economy, education, social and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
According government statistics, only 169 parliament
representatives-elect out of 485 remained valid as of May this
year. The other 316 include those who resigned, died and
disqualified or canceled.
</P>
<P>
Of the 169 who remained valid, 110 were from NLD. 
</P>
</TEXT>
