<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> June Inflation Down to 3.9 Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine's year-on-year inflation
declined slightly in June to 3.9 percent from 4.1 percent in May
following a slowdown for food and services, the government said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time this year that inflation registered a
decline, bringing the January-June average to 3.5 percent, the
National Statistics Office (NSO) said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in the first half of this year was also well
below the government's 5 percent to 6 percent goal for the whole
year, the government agency added.
</P>
<P>
Compared to June last year, tuition fee increases are
relatively less, resulting in the slowdown in inflation for
services, the NSO noted.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, lower prices of food items in Metro Manila,
particularly rice, fish, fruits and vegetables, contributed to the
situation.
</P>
<P>
However, the NSO said, higher month-on-month inflation in the
indexes of services and miscellaneous items resulted in a 0.7
percent increase in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
