<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Thai Opposition Party to Quit Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Another main opposition party of
Thailand, the Social Action Party (SAP), has decided to have its
19 members of parliament (MPs) quit the House of Representatives
in three days, further diminishing the opposition's presence in
the House, the Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, at least nine of the MPs are set to defy the decision
and the SAP threatens to expel them from the party.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the nine MPs, though technically still
under the SAP's roof, are no longer in the opposition since they
were poised to defect to the coalition parties Chart Pattana and
Seritham.
</P>
<P>
The New Aspiration Party (NAP), the largest opposition party,
will also push for the resignation of 34 dissident MPs who plan to
defect.
</P>
<P>
These 34 MPs remained in the House, ignoring the party's
pulling-out resolution at the end of last month. About 50 NAP MPs
resigned from the parliament in an effort to push for an immediate
House dissolution and an early election.
</P>
<P>
If all the NAP and SAP rebels are expelled from their parties,
they will automatically lose their MP status and thus leave the
House without an opposition.
</P>
<P>
However, they can put up a legal fight by citing article 47 of
the constitution, which allows them to appeal to the Constitution
Court if they feel their parties' decisions obstruct their
legitimate parliamentary duties.
</P>
<P>
With about half of SAP MPs poised to resign from parliament and
the remaining opposition MPs considered de-facto "government MPs",
pressure for an immediate House dissolution is expected to mount
again, but whether it will reach the point of forcing the prime
minister to actually call a new election remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai was quoted as saying that he had
anticipated the outcome of SAP's decision and he would not
dissolve the House as long as there were still some opposition MPs
left.
</P>
<P>
The government insists that it will not dissolve the parliament
until the budget bill for fiscal year 2001 and the amendments to
the election laws are passed by the House.
</P>
<P>
The government has to call a general election before November
when its term ends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
