<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Aid to Bangladesh Decreases Sharply in Fiscal 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Flow of foreign aid was 41 percent
less during the first 11 months of fiscal 1999-2000 than that in
the corresponding period of the previous year, The Daily Star
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign aid was 1.2 billion U.S. dollars from July
1999 to May 2000 against 2.05 billion dollars in the corresponding
period of fiscal 1998-1999, sources in the Economic Relation
Division ERD) said
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry sources said the flow of foreign aid,
particularly food aid, was very high in fiscal 1998-1999 because
of the devastating flood in the country, worth 269.8 million
dollars. It came down to 50.5 million dollars in the following
year.
</P>
<P>
Food aid is declining also because donors are reluctant to
disburse food aid as the country is nearing food autarky, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1999-2000, the disbursement of aid is also far less
than the donors' commitments. ERD estimates show that donors
pledged 2.04 billion dollars, but the disbursement was only 1.2
billion dollars till May this year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria in his budget speech
announced an annual development program of 175 billion taka (3.36
billion dollars) for fiscal 2000-2001, more than 49 percent of
which was projected to come from external sources.
</P>
<P>
Evaluating the aid flow, the ministry sources said the
government will have to go for massive borrowing to fulfill the
target for the development program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
