<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Form Workers' Welfare Committee in EPZs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will form
a workers' welfare committee in the Export Processing Zones (EPZs)
as an interim measure before introducing full rights of trade
union activities there, The Financial Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A high-level meeting held at the Board of Investment (BOI)
Tuesday took the decision aimed at solving the thorny issue of
allowing trade union activities in the country's EPZs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting observed that workers in the EPZs would get all
facilities under the new system which they usually get through
trade unions.
</P>
<P>
It hoped the setting up of the committee would solve all the
problems relating to rights of trade union activities.
</P>
<P>
Besides forming the welfare committee, the government is making
preparations to face the hearing in the office of the U.S. Trade
Representative in Washington where Bangladesh will explain its
position. A high-level government delegation will be sent to
defend the country's stand.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh remains under strong pressure from the U.S.
government to allow trade union activities in the EPZs following a
petition from the American Federation of Labor and Congress for
Industrial Organization (AFL-CIO).
</P>
<P>
The AFL-CIO submitted a petition to the U.S. government to
cancel Generalized System of Preference facilities on Bangladesh
exports if trade union activities are not allowed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, major investors in the EPZs, including South Korea
and Japan, expressed their grave concern over the U.S. move,
terming it a conspiracy to destroy the investment-friendly
environment in the EPZs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
