<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish, Norwegian Prime Ministers Pledge Cooperation on Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Poland and Norway signed an accord
Monday to expand Polish purchase of Norwegian natural gas and
build a new pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Under the document signed by prime ministers Jens Stoltenberg
of Norway and Jerzy Buzek of Poland, the two countries will
conclude a contract this year and build a pipeline via the Baltic
sea that could deliver 5 billion cubic meters of natural gas
annually starting from 2004 or 2005.
</P>
<P>
Norway will provide Poland with 4 billion cubic meters of
natural gas before 2010, and the amount is expected to double in
2020.
</P>
<P>
Polish and Norwegian gas companies signed a contract last year
for gas supplies, with the first high-volume deliveries due to
reach Poland in October.
</P>
<P>
Poland consumes 11 billion cubic meters of gas every year, two
thirds of which is imported from Russia. Poland's buying gas from
Norway is seen as an attempt to wean itself from dependence on
Russian supplies.
</P>
<P>
Stoltenberg, who is on an official two-day visit to Poland, met
parliament speakers during his visit and traveled to the city of
Gdansk.
</P>
<P>
Stoltenberg's visit has also seen the signing of an agreement
on converting 27 million U.S. dollars, part of Polish debt to
Norway, into investment in environment-related projects in Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
