<HEADLINE> Xinhua Economic News Summary at 0400 GMT, July 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq will not cut its own oil production to combat
Saudi Arabia's move to increase oil output by 500,000 million
barrels per day (bpd), Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil output is now monitored by the United Nations, not
by the OPEC. It now produces 3 million barrels of oil a day, and
its oil output level will be increased to 3.3 million bpd by the
end of the year and to 4 million bpd by next year. (Iraq-Oil
Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's trade surplus will reach 1.1 billion U.S.
dollars, less than the government's preliminary target of 2.8
billion dollars, said the National Industry Confederation (NIC)
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The organization forecasted that the South American country's
exports will be 54.3 billion dollars, increasing 13 percent over
1999; imports will be 53.2 billion dollars, 8 percent over last
year. The gross domestic product (GDP) will increase by 4 percent,
mainly estimated by the industrial sector, which will grow 6
percent this year. (Brazil-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Europe's major stock markets ended lower Tuesday, as
weak oil stocks dragged London market lower.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index slipped 53.4 points, or 0.8 percent to
6415.8, a day after rising 2.5 percent in its largest one-day
point gain this year. The oil sector was under pressure after
Saudi Arabia announced plans to boost oil production to try to
bring prices down. Brent crude oil fell 1.04 U.S. dollars to 30.06
per barrel in London. (EU-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
