<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Police Seize 104 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Austrian police seized 104 kilograms
of heroin at the Schwechat airport last month, security
authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The heroin was found inside 102 cartons loaded with textile
goods coming from Turkey, security officials said.
</P>
<P>
The drug, valued at 20 million U.S. dollars on the black market,
was the biggest seizure ever by Austrian police.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of a Turkish drug trafficker earlier last month on
the Norway-Sweden border provided clues for the seizure, according
to the officials.
</P>
<P>
Two Austrian suspects and five others from Turkey and Sweden
have been detained so far. Austrian officials believe that a big
drug-trafficking ring is behind the case.
</P>
<P>
International drug-trafficking rings are more often using
European airports for drug transfer, said officials from the
Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released in June by the European
Commission, 20 tons of drugs, including 340 kilograms of heroin,
were confiscated at European airports in 1999, and 3,000 people
were arrested, 80 percent of them passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria to Hold Referendum on EU Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang
Schuessel announced a plan Tuesday evening to hold a nationwide
referendum on the European Union's sanctions against the country.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel said that the decision to hold the referendum was
reached after six hours of discussion by the coalition government
comprising the Freedom Party and the People's Party. He said if
the EU would not lift its sanctions in the fall, the national
referendum will be held in October or November.
</P>
<P>
In the plan, the Austrian coalition government also asked the
EU to ensure equal rights and duties of all EU member countries
and guarantee basic rights on electing their governments and
opposed the attempts of a few big countries to dominate other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the far-right Freedom Party joined the coalition
government, 14 EU member countries began to impose sanctions on
Austria in February. At the end of June, the EU decided to keep
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The idea for a referendum was first proposed by former leader
of the Freedom Party, Joerg Haider, in April, but it was opposed
by the People's Party. Since the sanctions continue, specially
when France, a main proponent of sanctions against Austria, took
over the EU's rotating presidency on July 1, the People's Party
changed its attitude. In May the Austrian government worked out an
18-point policy including the plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the referendum aims to exert pressure on
the EU. But other Austrian parties are against the decision.
Austrian President Thomas Klestil said that he was afraid the
referendum would instigate anti-EU emotion in his country.
Austrian opposition parties said the plebiscite could not help
lift the sanctions, but only waste money.
</P>
<P>
Portugal's foreign minister warned last month that the
referendum means suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire Imposes Curfew Following Army Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Cote d'Ivoire imposed a curfew
Tuesday evening after troops took to the streets, firing in the
air and demanding money from the ruling military junta for their
part in the December 24 coup, reports from Abidjan said.
</P>
<P>
The curfew will run from 7:00 p.m. (1900 GMT) until 6:00 a.m. (
0600 GMT).
</P>
<P>
In a communique, the National Committee of Public Salvation
said the restrictions were imposed "because of present
circumstances" and called on everyone to "scrupulously respect
this exceptional measure."
</P>
<P>
Soldiers moved onto the streets before dawn on Tuesday, who,
witnesses said, later commandeered private vehicles.
</P>
<P>
In the northern cities of Bouake and Korhogo, mutineers looted
banks.
</P>
<P>
By nightfall, calm had returned to Abidjan, the commercial
capital of this west African country, apart from occasional
gunshots.
</P>
<P>
In December, junior soldiers staged a coup, the first since the
country's independence from France in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers demanding a bonus for their role in the December coup
were reportedly behind Tuesday's events.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address, military ruler General Robert Guei said,
"I remain open to dialogue. You can send your delegations to me."
</P>
<P>
He said Tuesday's acts threatened to tarnish the army's image
and would lead to soldiers being blacklisted.
</P>
<P>
He said his government had already fulfilled promises on pay
and was in the process of delivering promises of help for soldiers
to own their own homes.
</P>
<P>
However, Guei denied having promised to grant 6 million CFA (8,
700 U.S. dollars to each soldier for their part in the coup.
</P>
<P>
National television afterwards broadcast a statement by a
corporal, Aboubakary Kone, who called on all soldiers to return to
barracks, saying he had received assurances from the president
that "all our grievances will be satisfied."
</P>
<P>
"From today (Tuesday) a commission composed of members from
each force will be formed to put in motion the measures taken by
the president of the republic regarding the total satisfaction of
our claims," said the corporal, who is the mutineers' spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
