<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Council of Women Set to Safeguard Women's Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Council of Women
will promote all causes that safeguard women's social status,
development and health, said Pnina Herzog, the newly-elected
secretary-general of the council, at a triennial plenary session
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
She added the council will adhere to the principles of equality
and not interfering in the internal affairs of its member states.
</P>
<P>
The most important way of functioning for the council is to
cooperate with the United Nations to safeguard women's rights and
interests and promote world peace, she added.
</P>
<P>
Finnish President Tarja Halonen said at the opening ceremony of
the session that women and children are always among the first to
suffer from poverty in the world, and that gender discrimination,
lack of education and improper medical treatment have inflicted a
vast amount of tragedies on women.
</P>
<P>
The most crucial thing to do at present is to guarantee basic
education for female children, the President added.
</P>
<P>
The five-day session, which started from Sunday and is being
attended by more than 300 representatives from about 40 member
states, has elected a new council and admitted five new members
including Ukraine, Burundi, Azerbaijan and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, safeguarding the rights and interests of women
in developing countries has become a focus for the council, which
was founded in 1888. 
</P>
</TEXT>
