<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are today's
highlights of major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China and Tajikistan on Tuesday vowed to further coordinate
their efforts within bilateral and multilateral frameworks to
fight against national separatism, international terrorism and
extremism.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement signed in Dushanbe, Tajikistan, by
visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his Tajik counterpart,
Emomali Rakhmonov, shortly after their talks, the two countries
said they believe national separatism, international terrorism and
religious extremism constitute grave menace to the security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Discussing a piece of legislation to give more power to the
customs to help them crack down harder on smuggling, Chinese
lawmakers also voiced concern Tuesday that their behavior should
be more closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
Citing recent notorious cases in which senior customs officials
were involved, Tao Siju, member of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, proposed that more stipulations should be
provided for the supervision of customs officers, as well as
measures to prevent and punish their deeds of malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- China's central authorities have called for speeding up the
healthy development of small towns in the country's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party and the
State Council have jointly issued a document entitled "Suggestions
on Promoting the Healthy Development of Small Towns," outlining
the principles for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government has allowed commercial banks to take
care of the payroll of public servants nationwide since July 1
this year, the Ministry of Finance announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a release from the ministry, government
institutions will no longer pay their employees directly. Instead,
the treasury will allocate funds to the banks, which will put the
money into the accounts of public servants.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji said during his one-day official visit in
Luxembourg on Monday that Chinese leaders appreciate Luxembourg's
push for dialogue with China to resolve differences between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
-- The issuance of a new version of banknotes in Taiwan will
not change its status as part of China's territory, a Taiwan
Affairs Office of the State Council spokesman said in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
A new version of local currency went into circulation on Monday,
with a so-called "central bank" replacing the former "Bank of
Taiwan" as the issuer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
