<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils New Police Powers to Combat Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- British police will be given new
powers to crack down on suspected football hooligans, Home
Secretary (Interior Minister) Jack Straw has announced.
</P>
<P>
Ministers desperate to stop thugs causing mayhem during the
2002 World Cup qualifying tournament, which starts later this year,
hope to rush through the legislation before Parliament breaks for
its summer recess on July 28.
</P>
<P>
Action was promised after violence marred England's Euro 2000
games and will require the co-operation of the Tory opposition to
go through in time.
</P>
<P>
Straw told MPs that football hooliganism abroad was no longer
confined to a "small minority of troublemakers".
</P>
<P>
In future anyone who receives a banning order will be subject
to both domestic and international bans, he said.
</P>
<P>
Everyone subject to a ban would have to surrender their
passport while major overseas games were on.
</P>
<P>
Police would also be given new powers to prevent a person from
leaving the country where officers believed they were out to cause
trouble abroad, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
