<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Well-Preserved Volcano Craters Found in Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 5 (Xinhua) --More than 50 well-preserved volcano
craters have been found near Qiongshan city in northern Hainan,
China's southernmost island province.
</P>
<P>
A group of Chinese geologists who have just made an inspection
trip to the area heralded the large number of craters, with intact
lava tunnels, as a modern geological museum of volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
Historical records say that some 70 million years ago, northern
Hainan had more than 30 volcanic eruptions, which produced the
craters. Some of the bigger ones have now been opened to tourists,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that provincial government departments have
also been preparing the site for inclusion on a list of geological
relics enjoying state protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Device Flushes Toilet with Glass of Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A newly developed device can wash
clean a toilet with only a glass of water.
</P>
<P>
The device can wash down waste efficiently by spraying about 0.
2 liters of high-pressure water each time. Water that has been
used to wash vegetables or clothes can be used to clean the toilet
with the device.
</P>
<P>
The device will help save some 12 liters of water for each
cleaning, according to its inventor, the Jinniu Environmental
Protection Equipment Plant of Dashiqiao city in northeast China's
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of the water tanks of toilets in China ranges from
nine to 13 liters, while the international standard is six liters.
Flush toilets are becoming popular in urban areas in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 400 of China's 668 cities are facing water
shortages, and of them more than 100 are seriously threatened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tourists Flock to Haikou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- This capital of southernmost China's
island province of Hainan expects to have hosted 1.55 million
domestic and overseas tourists in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a local official, this figure is 19.7 percent up
over the same period last year, as Haikou raked in about 1.29
billion yuan (about 156 million U.S. dollars) in earnings from
tourism in January-June, accounting for 19 percent of the city's
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Haikou, on the northern tip of the island, is some 35 km away
from the Leizhou Peninsula of Guangdong Province. The promising
tourism prospects have been attributed to the fact that in the
past few years, Haikou has invested more on improving urban
transportation and other infrastructure, and building more tourism
facilities. It has also been working hard to become an
international tourism city.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the local Meilan International Airport, built at
an expense of 2.4 billion yuan (about 289 million dollars), has
been in service since May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Visitors to this southernmost province mainly come by plane,
but construction of a railway tunnel that will link Hainan with
Guangdong is underway. The project will be completed and put into
use next year at a cost of more than four billion yuan (about 482
million dollars), local sources claim.  
</P>
</TEXT>
