<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Wishes Clinton-Arafat-Barak Summit Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein on
Wednesday hoped for substantial progress in the upcoming summit by
the United States, Israel and the Palestinians over the Middle East
peace.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Abdullah hoped the summit, scheduled for July
11 at Camp David near Washington, will result in an agreement which
will guarantee both the legitimate rights of the Palestinians and
the peace and stability for all peoples in the region.
</P>
<P>
The king called on all parties concerned to exert their utmost
efforts to pave the way for a success of the summit and for a just,
durable and comprehensive peace on the Palestinian track of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah al-
Khatib
said Jordan is looking forward to a success of the three-way
summit,
which will meet the aspirations for peace of all peoples in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib noted that a just and durable solution to the
Palestinian issue is the corner stone for the Middle East peace
process and for peaceful co-existences of all peoples in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated Jordan's principled support for the
legitimate rights of the Palestinians, including self-determination
and the establishment of an independent state on their own soil.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been pursuing a peace policy toward all neighboring
countries since it signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, the
second Arab country, following Egypt, to reach a peace deal with
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Jordan has been a major peace broker between Israel
and its Arab neighbors. 
</P>
