<HEADLINE> Ankara Condemns Attack on Turkish Consulate in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Foreign Ministry
Wednesday condemned a bomb attack on the Turkish consulate on the
Greek island of Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred in the early morning hours when
unidentified assailants hurled a gasoline bomb at the balcony on
the roof of the consulate, causing minor damage.
</P>
<P>
"We express regret over and condemn the incident," said the
ministry in a statement issued after the attack. "We consider it an
event that runs counter to the current development of relations
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Embassy in Athens on Wednesday morning presented a
note to the Greek authorities demanding that the culprits be
arrested as soon as possible and duly punished, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey also demanded that measures be adopted to guarantee the
safety of the Turkish diplomatic establishments in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, locked in disputes over Cyprus and the Aegean
Sea for decades, began to improve their relations last year after
both countries were hit by devastating earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
The rapprochement was furthered during an exchange of visits to
each other's country by foreign ministers of the two countries
earlier this year, which resulted in a series of trust-building
bilateral agreements.
</P>
<P>
Rhodes, a Greek tourist resort, is located off Turkey's Aegean
coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
