<HEADLINE> Chile Rejects Media Transmission of Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Chile's Supreme Court ministers
plenum decided Wednesday not to authorize radio or television
transmission of the upcoming allegations about the appeal against
the annulment of the privileges of the former military ruler of
this country, Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
The public and the communication media will be left in the dark
about the details of the pro and con allegations in the Pinochet
case, as it happened in April and May of this year in the Santiago
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
The Santiago Court of Appeals ruled in first instance on May
23 to annul Pinochet parliamentary immunity to investigate his
possible participation in the so-called case of the "Caravan of
Death" during his mandate.
</P>
<P>
On June 9 of this year, a few days after learning of the
Santiago Court of Appeals decision, Pinochet filed before the
Supreme Court, through his lawyer, an appeal to the annulation of
this legislative privilege.
</P>
<P>
Supreme Court President Hernan Alvarez said last week that on
July 5, 6, and 7 the allegations pro and against Pinochet would
be heard, but they were postponed for next Wednesday in the
Supreme Court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
