<HEADLINE> U.S. Promotional Products Industry Tripled in Ten Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Continuing a 10-year trend,
distributor sales of promotional products in the United States
have reached record levels, a trade group reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sales of promotional products for 1999 registered nearly 15
billion U.S. dollars, a 13 percent increase over 1998. This figure
round out a 10-year growth rate that tripled the size of the
industry, which sold 5 billion dollars in 1990, said Promotional
Products Association International (PPAI), quoting a new annual
survey of 13,000 distributors in the country.
</P>
<P>
Promotional products, which consists of useful items often
imprinted with a company or organization's logo, name or message,
are a popular marketing tool used by virtually every business in
the United States to help communicate advertising messages.
</P>
<P>
For the 14th consecutive year, wearable items such as T-shirts,
caps, jackets and headwear were the most popular product category,
with almost 30 percent of all sales, according to PPAI. Other
promotional products categories include writing instruments (pens,
pencils, markers, etc), desk/office/business accessories (such as
briefcases, folders and desk pen sets), calendars, bags, and
sporting goods and travel accessories. Business gifts were the
most commonly relied upon programmatic usage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
