<HEADLINE> Europe's Major Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets closed
mixed Wednesday, as the latest profit warnings from the U.S.
spooked the technology sector and lower oil prices knocked down
energy stocks.
</P>
<P>
Oil giant BP Amoco and banking stocks dragged London's FTSE 100
lower for the second consecutive day, countering telecom gains.
The benchmark index closed down 34.5 points, or 0.54 percent to
6382.5.
</P>
<P>
Financial stocks accounted for three of the top four percentage
losers on the FTSE 100. Royal Bank of Scotland slipped 5 percent
and Barclays fell 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco fell 5.6 percent as crude oil prices continued to
decline following Saudi Arabia's decision Tuesday to boost output.
Brent crude oil for August delivery was down 36 cents at 29.22 US
dollars a barrel in late trading.
</P>
<P>
The electronically traded Xetra Dax in Frankfurt ended up 17.37
points, or 0.25 percent, at 6961.73, but still below an earlier
gain of 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Paris stock ended with a half percent loss as tech sector was
hit heavily. The benchmark CAC 40 index closed down 0.49 percent
or 32.70 points at 6462.70.
</P>
