<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Announces 2000 Population Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The 2000 United Nations
Population Award was announced here Wednesday and the winners were
Professor Ismail Awadallah Sallam, Minister of Health and
Population of Egypt and the Mexican Foundation for Family Planning
(MEXFAM).
</P>
<P>
Professor Sallam, since he became Egypt's Minister of Health
and Population, has brought into the government of Egypt what is
already a lifetime's experience and engagement in the health
issues of his country. His contribution in the field of population,
especially from the bio-medical perspective, has earned the
respect of practitioners and experts alike.
</P>
<P>
His personal commitment to preventive health, and to making
basic health care available to the poor and under-served, has
helped improve the lives of people throughout Egypt.
</P>
<P>
His active support for family planning initiatives and health
initiatives and health package to meet the basic needs of mothers
and children serves to benefit not only them, but also the health
of succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
MEXFAM, a pioneer among the Nongovernmental Organizations in
the fields of family planning and sexual and reproductive health.
For the past 25 yeas, MEXFAM has worked to help bring about
legislation that placed family planning firmly on Mexico's public
health agenda.
</P>
<P>
It has been one of Latin America's leading agents in education
and medical services for adolescent sexual health. It devised a
unique and comprehensive strategy for youth that combines peer
training, strengthening of community resources, health education
materials and school-based workshops. Today, that strategy is
being used and effectively in many Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, U.N. Deputy Secretary-General,
Frechette Louis, said these awards demonstrated the world has
understood that addressing population issues was an integral part
of the social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Secretary-General expressed the hope that the
leadership of these Laureates would serve as inspiration to
countless other harbingers of hope, for the benefit of millions of
men, women and children throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The prize was created in 1981.  
</P>
</TEXT>
