<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DSL to Overtake Cable, Says U.S. Think Tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The demand for high-speed
Internet access will increase from 2.3 million subscribers in the
United States last year to 42 million in 2005, a U.S. technology
research think tank predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There are two technologies available today that allow low-price
multi-megabit data transfer rates -- digital subscriber line (DSL)
and cable modem. So far, cable has been the leader, due in part to
its earlier market entry. As of the end of 1999, high-speed cable
Internet service had 2.1 million U.S. subscribers, while DSL only
had 500,000 subscribers, according to Allied Business Intelligence
(ABI).
</P>
<P>
But DSL could overtake cable modem soon. In the first quarter
this year, some DSL providers in the U.S. were seeing 50 percent
to 60 percent increases in subscription rates. ABI said that the
demand for DSL would maintain such an increase for at least
another year.
</P>
<P>
In the coming year, DSL will rise in popularity due to
aggressive advertising campaigns by DSL providers. As the
subscriber base grows and the industry learns how to deploy DSL
efficiently and economically, the waiting lists will shrink. Right
now, however, the local exchange carriers cannot deploy the DSL
service fast enough. Some providers are already experiencing
significant backlogs because they lack skilled technicians. ABI
said this should be resolved by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
According to ABI, broadband subscribers worldwide will jump
from 5 million in 1999 to 91 million in 2005, a compound average
annual growth rate of 160 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000705.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
