of the (police) in some areas of Belfast tonight," the Reuters
quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's police chief Ronnie Flanagan warned earlier
that Protestant hardliners planned to launch bomb and gun attacks.
</P>
<P>
As Flanagan issued his warning, riot police in armored vehicles
drove back 60 masked youths in a Protestant loyalist" stronghold
near Belfast's city center after they had hijacked a bus and tried
to use it as a street barricade.
</P>
<P>
Protestant hardliners, furious at a ban on a Protestant parade
through a Roman Catholic enclave, also set cars and barricades on
fire in the province's capital, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
A steel barrier was also erected at Drumcree as security forces
in Northern Ireland brace themselves for another night of trouble.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, shots were fired in Belfast, and in Drumcree a
water-cannon was used on protesters for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The barrier, 20ft high and 30ft wide, was made up of huge steel
containers filled with concrete and topped with barbed wire and
was put in place at Drumcree bridge by army engineers.
</P>
<P>
It was expected to stay in place until after this weekend's
main march. 
