<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The technology stocks fell sharply
Wednesday as software makers including Computer Associates
International warned that they will miss profit expectations.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index closed down 128.83
at 3,863.10. The Dow Jones industrial average also fell 77.07 at
10,483.60.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
index fell 23.31 at 1,446.23.
</P>
<P>
Computer Associates warned Wall Street investors that the
company will not meet earnings expectations in the second quarter.
Its shares fell 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, BMC Software said its earnings will be 18 to 21
cents a share in the second quarter, much less than 46 cents in
expectations. its shares also fell 25.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The selloff spread the whole market because the warnings raised
fears that other companies will issue disappointing earnings
results later on.
</P>
<P>
The market was also damaged by the expectations in the Intel's
growth slowdown in the next six to nine months from Salomon Smith
Barney and the downgrade of Oracle stocks from "buy" to "market
performer" by J.P. Morgan. Both Intel and Oracle fell.
</P>
<P>
The latest data showing the slowdown in the U.S. economy failed
to stop the selling. The Conference Board, a prominent business
research group, reported that the Composite Index of Leading
Economic Indicators declined by 0.1 percent in May in response to
six hikes in interest rates by the Federal Reserve in the past
year. The report raised hope that the Federal Reserve will leave
rates unchanged at the August 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.29 at 644.90 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 21.69 at 921.71. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 5.79 at 518.25.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the new York Stock Exchange, with 1,486 up, 1,477 down and 412
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.003 billion shares today from 446.76
million in the previously shortened session.
</P>
<P>
The stock market was closed at 1 p.m. on Monday and shut down
on Tuesday for the U.S. Independence Day holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
