<HEADLINE> Brazil Expects to Be Oil Self-Sufficient By 2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Brazil expects to become self-
sufficient in oil by the year 2005, said Wednesday Mines and
Energy Minister Rodolpho Tourinho.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the government goal is to achieve by
2005 a balance between supply and demand, which he considers
feasible.
</P>
<P>
The state oil company Petrobras president Henri Philippe
Rischtul said that present Brazilian oil consumption is about 1.75
million barrels a day (bpd) , which could rise to 2.2 million bpd
by 2005, if the economy grows at a rate of four percent per year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil produced last year an average of 1.132 million bpd . The
goal is 1.85 million bpd by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras signed Wednesday an agreement with foreign investors
for 4.45 billion dollars for oil exploration and production
projects in two oil fields in the Campos Watershed, the main oil
producing zone in the north of the Rio de Janeiro state, and where
oil output reached Friday last week a record of one million
barrels a day.  
