<HEADLINE> 2 Die From Heat-Stroke in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Two people died from heat-stroke in
the northern Greek town of Yiannina as temperatures throughout the
country soared to 44 degrees Celsius Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two people, a man and a woman in their 50s, were the first
victims of a heatwave sweeping through Greece as of Sunday, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Public Power Corporation (DEH) reported demand
for electricity had reached 8,060 MWATT, the highest ever recorded
on any single day, but Greek Development Minister Nikos
Christodoulakis said that the country's power grid was well
prepared to meet the extra demand.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the hottest summers for Greece in a decade and
the temperatures are expected to remain at the same levels in
coming days.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the possible problems stemming from the heatwave,
the country's hospitals, health centers and ambulance services
have made themselves ready for emergencies while state and
municipal air-conditioned sports grounds and halls have been made
available to heat sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The country's fire brigade is also in a heightened state of
preparation, having stepped up patrols of the forested hills
around Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
