<HEADLINE> Security Council to Vote on Sierra Leone Diamonds Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council,
after several days of delay, on Wednesday evening will vote on a
draft resolution to impose a global embargo on diamond exports
from Sierra Leone, where a gems-for-guns trade is financing a
civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will cast the vote following its closed-
door discussions over the past few days. The draft resolution,
initiated by Britain, would ban all rough diamonds from Sierra
Leone until the government of the West African nation could set up
a proper certification system for the gems -- as well as regain
access to lucrative diamond-mining areas under the control of the
rebel United Revolutionary Front.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution put to vote said the embargo will be
imposed for an initial period of 18 months, suggested by France,
rather than 36 months as the United States prefers, U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Mali, one of the 15 Security Council members, is expected to
vote in abstentions, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Diamonds, gold, iron ore and bauxite accounted for about two
thirds of Sierra Leone's exports before war in the 1990s wrecked
the economy of the West African country. Rebels control some 90
percent of the diamond mines, which yield among the best stones in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
